status_message: The funeral prayers in absentia being held for Manzoor Ahmad Dar, 14 years after his enforced disappearance, at Rawalpora Srinagar, 19 January 2016. Dar, a resident of Rawalpora, was picked up by personnel of 35 Rashtriya Riffles lead by Major Kishore Malhotra during the intervening night of 18th and 19th January 2002. Special Investigation Team (SIT) of J&K police closed the case in November last year, presuming that Dar has been killed in Army custody. Police invoked murder charges against Major Malhotra. Rising Kashmir / Farooq Javed

status_message:
Avoid packaging of food items in newspapers
Rising Kashmir News
Srinagar: Additional Commissioner, food safety Srinagar in a communiqué has advised people to avoid the packaging of food articles particularly hot fried items in newspapers because newspaper ink may contaminate food articles resulting into serious health complications.
As in Food Safety and Standards Act 2006, the use of synthetic Food Colours is restricted to certain beverages and bakery items.
Strict action under relevant provisions of Food Safety & Standards Act 2006 shall be initiated against violators.

status_message: People pray at the mosque adjacent to the shrine of Shah-e-Hamdan in Srinagar on Monday, 21 September 2015. Hundreds of Muslims thronged to the shrine to commemorate the death anniversary of famous Sufi saint Mir Syed Ali Hamadani in old part of Srinagar. The shrine of Shah-e-Hamdan or Khanqah-e-Moulla is one of the oldest Muslim shrines in the region. The saint Hamadani was Iranian and visited Kashmir various times in the 14th century and played an influential role in the spread of Islam in Kashmir.Rising Kashmir/Farooq Javed

status_message: University of Kashmir launched an eight-week course for the learning of German language at Bakshi Imtiyaz Alam Summer Institute of Foreign Languages (BIASIFL) on Wednesday, July 22, 2015. The institute has been named after senior journalist and former chief copy editor of Rising Kashmir, who taught German language at the University of Kashmir's Institute of Foreign Languages and Tourism department, and passed away on May 15, 2015. The summer training course would be sponsored by Bakshi's United States-based sister Prof. Tasneem Bakshi Rosner. Photos/Rising Kashmir

status_message: Hilal Ahmad War and Javed Ahmed Mir leaders of  All Parties Hurriyat Conference (M ) were detained by police during a protest in Srinagar on Monday 13 July 2015. Authorities imposed strict restrictions in some parts of downtown area of Srinagar and put separatist leaders under house arrest to thwart their rally on eve of martyrs' day in Kashmir. Every year, the 13 July in restive Kashmir, is observed as Martyrs' day to pay homage to the people who were killed in 1931 by the troopers of the then Dogra ruler Maharaja Hari Singh.Rising Kashmir/Farooq Javed

Srinagar’s children park endangers lives.
Children’s play has long been considered to have a key role in their well-being and the development of their future life, but a children’s park situated in the heart of Srinagar city, meant for recreation and amusement of children, is putting their lives at greater risks. 
Owing to the official indifference the park named ‘Gulshan-e-Atfaal’ mean¬ing ‘Garden for Kids’ just adjacent to Allama Iqbal Park is in essence ‘Danger for Kids’ because the slides and swings here are damaged and corrugated. Rising Kashmir/Farooq Shah

Parthiv Shah, a photographer, filmmaker and graphic designer Tuesday visited  Rising Kashmir newsroom to talked about images and art of photography with the journalists and photojournalist. 
Shah is an alumnus of the National Institute of Design, India, the University of California, Davis and visiting scholar at the SOAS, London University. He has made several documentary films, curated exhibitions and has several photo-books to his credit. Growing up in a family of artists and through his own professional training, he brings an interesting intersection of art, photography and design to his work. Rising Kashmir/Shuaib Masoodi

status_message: Policemen detained a member of government Urban Local Bodies Employees United Forum (ULBEUF) during a protest march in Srinagar on Tuesday, 09 June 2015.  Police used baton charge and detained a dozen members of  ULBEUF. They were planning to encircle the civil Secretariat which houses the offices of Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister Mufti Muhammad Syeed's and top bureaucrats, to protest against government's decision to ban local bodies at tourist places Pahalgam and Gulmarg. They were also demanding implementation of service recruitment rules  and regularisation of daily wagers and consolidated employees. Rising Kashmir/Farooq Javed

status_message:
Imtiyaz's Jinaza at 3.30 PM today
Rising Kashmir News
Srinagar : Nimaz-e-Jinaza of senior journalist Imtiyaz Bakhshi will be offered at 3.30 PM at his Buchwara residence, family sources said. 

Bakhshi passed away last evening. He had worked with Indian Express, Sahara Group and Rising Kashmir before he took a partial retirement due to ailment.

status_message: A vehicle passing through a snow bound Zojila pass, 108 kilometers east of Srinagar on Wednesday,13 May 2015. The Srinagar-Leh road link was thrown open for vehicular traffic after around five months. Border Roads Organisation (BRO) which maintains the road opened it after clearing the snow from Zojila Pass, 3630 meters above sea level. The 434-km long road was closed following the heavy snowfall in December end. Photo/Rising Kashmir

status_message: Protesters throw stones at police and CRPF during a protest in Narbal on the outskirts of Srinagar on Saturday,18 April 2015. Suhail Ahmad Sofi, a teenager was killed when Police opened fire at a group of protesters who were pelting stones at them during a protest Police accepted that their officials had violated Standard Operating Procedures (SOP) while dealing with the protesters and have lodged a case against the guilty policemen. Hurriyat Conference led by Syed Ali Geelani had given a shutdown call against the detention of Masrat Alam, killing of another youth Khalid Muzaffar allegedly by Army in south Kashmir's Tral area and for protesting the role of 'biased' of New Del,hi and Mumbia based media channels. Rising Kashmir/Farooq Javed

Srinagar, Mar 29: At least 44 structures including 18 residential houses were damaged due to landslides caused by heavy rainfall in Kashmir over the past 24 hours, police said today.

 

A landslide caused by the rain in Chontinar village of central Kashmir Budgam district destroyed eight residential houses and 10 cowsheds last evening.

 

At least 26 residential houses were partially damaged by the landslide but there were no reports of loss of life, they said.

 

The incident has created panic among people about possibility of fresh floods in the valley, police said, adding that the residents of the area were evacuated to safety before the landslide struck.

CM on way to Srinagar to personally monitor the situation arising out of incessant rains in Valley 

Govt monitoring water levels, No need to panic: Dy CM 

            JAMMU, MARCH 29: The Chief Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed is on way to Srinagar to personally monitor the situation arising due to incessant rains in the Valley.

Meanwhile, Deputy Chief Minister, Dr. Nirmal Singh informed the Legislative Assembly that administration is on full alert in the wake of heavy rains in valley and the situation is being monitored continuously. He said people should not panic and assured that all precautionary measures have been put in place.

          Giving the latest update by 11 A.M, Deputy Chief Minister informed that the water level at Sangam stands at 12 feet against the alarm level of 18 feet. At Ram Munshibagh the water level stands at 12.6 feet against alarm level of 16 feet, while as at Asham the water level has been recorded as 8.50 feet against alarm level of 30 feet.

The Deputy Chief Minister said the water levels are being relayed to the control room on regular basis and right now there is no need for panic.

status_message:
Man “involved in flesh trade” shot dead in Bijbehara
Shah Suhail 
Anantnag: Unidentified gunmen fired upon a person, identified as Javiad Ahmed Waza, resident of Bijbehara Colony at his home this evening. 
Javaid was immediately rushed to SDH Bijbehara by his family, where he reportedly succumbed to his injuries. 
Waza was allegedly involved in flesh trade and was briefly detained under Public Safety Act after his involvement triggered protests from members of Civil Society of Bijbehara and religious heads.
Police acted under immense public pressure, booking Waza under PSA, after some of the victims alleged that police is trying to hush-up the case. 
Some agitated youth had also attacked and ransacked Waza's house after his involvement in flesh trade racket came to fore.

The people of Sonawari area of Bandipora district still have no access to pure drinking water. International World Water Day is observed annually on March 22 every year to highlight the importance of freshwater and its management. Rising Kashmir/ Sheikh Saleem.

status_message:
Draw of lots for selection of pilgrims held
RK News
Srinagar: Draw of lots (Qurrah) for selection of pilgrims of Hajj 2015 was held today at Hajj Committee of India Server at Mumbai with real time display on computer screens in the office of State Hajj Committee. The Deputy Commissioner, Srinagar, Additional Commissioner Kashmir, Executive Officer, J&K State Hajj Committee and a large number of pilgrims were present on the occasion.
Out of 29755 applicants, 2541 had been registered under Reserve Category A (pilgrims aged 70 year above) and 1946 under Reserve Category B (4th time applicants). As already notified, the State has got a quota of 6366 seats out of which 4487 pilgrims had been registered under Categories A and B, as mentioned above.
For remaining 1879 seats, the pilgrims have been provisionally selected on basis of draw of lots. Militants storm Police Station in Kathua
Two security personnel killed, 3 injured in fidayeen attack   
Jammu on high alert, Jammu-Pathankot highway closed
Syed Amjad Shah
Jammu: Atleast two policemen were killed and three others were wounded when a suicide squad of militants stormed Rajbagh Police Station in Kathua on Friday morning.
According to the sources, the militants in Army uniform stormed into the police station at 6 am opening indiscriminate firing in which one sentry who was on duty got hit by the bullets and died.
As the two security men including a police personal and a CRPF were hit by the bullets taking toll two casualties and three other police men wounded during the sudden firing. A police officer, wishing anonymity said it was not clear that one of the killed was a paramilitary personnel or policeman.
“Both the bodies (of security men) are still laying inside the police station. We cannot retrieve them from there since the area is under firing range of militants,” the police officer told Rising Kashmir.
They said the militants occupied the police station, while security forces blocked all entry and exit points to trap the suicide squad.
“Three men were seen in army uniform who forced entry inside the police station and took position,” sources said, adding that the Jammu Pathankot highway has been blocked for vehicular traffic and army along with other security agencies have started operation to eliminate the militants.
Though it was not clear, sources said, the ultras had infiltrated from Pakistan since the International Border is around 15 km away from the spot where they have carried out deadly strike.
Till the filling of this report, the encounter was on. 
Meanwhile, a high alter has been sounded in Jammu in view of attack and the police mela which has also been postponed. SSP Kathua and other senior police officials have reached the encounter site. 
Earlier this morning, PCR Kathua received a phone call about the militant attack following which they rushed flashed message in all the police station besides sharing information with the army and other agencies. No police official was available to give official statement.

Muneer-ul-Islam is new Director Information
RK News
Jammu: The cabinet which met on Sunday posted Muneer-ul-Islam Additional District Development Commissioner, Pulwama as the new Director Information. He replaces Mukhtar-ul-Aziz who has been posted as Mission Director, ICDS. 
More details awaited.

Major reshuffle in Civil, Police admin ordered
RK News
Jammu: The state cabinet that met with Chief MInister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed in chair today ordered a major reshuffle in civil and police administration.

Though formal orders are yet to be issued, sources said that Gazanfar Hussain has been posted as new Divisional Commissioner Kashmir replacing Rohit Kansal who has been posted as Commissioner/Secretary R & B. Pawan Kotwal is new Divisional Commissioner Jammu. Shantmanu goes to Health department while as Bipul Pathak to Housing and Urban. Tufail Mattoo is new Commissioner Srinagar Municipal Corporation. Sarmad Hafeez will head Lakes and Waterways Development Authority. Deputy Commissioners of Ganderbal and Baramulla are among many officers transferred.

In Police IGP (CID) B Sirinivas has been posted as IGP (Home Guards) replacing J P Singh who goes to Traffic. Javaid Gillani is new IGP Kashmir zone replacing A G Mir who is new IG (CID). Munir Khan has been transferred and posted as IG Crime. Daanish Rana is new IGP Jammu zone. Syed Ahfadul Mujtaba is new Director Special Security Group (SSG). A few more DIG’s have also been transferred. Details are awaited.

status_message:
IHC orders Lakhvi's release, India summons Pak envoy
Agencies
Islamabad: India today summoned the Pakistani envoy to convey its objection to a court ordering the release of Zaki-ur-Rehman Lakhvi, the man accused of plotting the 26/2011 Mumbai attacks.
Hours after the Islamabad High Court (IHC) ordered to release Lakhvi calling the detention illegal, Pakistan High Commissioner Abdul Basit was summoned by the foreign ministry.
India said it is Pakistan's responsibility to take all legal measures to ensure that he doesn't come out of jail.
Lakhvi, a top commander of the militant outfit Lashkar-e-Toiba has been in jail since 2009 over the attacks in Mumbai in which 166 people were killed.

Swine flu claims one more life in Kashmir
Manzoor-ul-Hassan  
Srinagar: One more H1N1 death was reported in last 24 hrs at SKIMS with three more patients tested positive which takes the number of cases 377 in Kashmir.
On Friday 54 cases were checked and 13 samples were taken including five from army hospital.
The deceased patient is a 42 yrs old female from Ganderbal. She was admitted a week ago with ARDS (Acute Respiratory Distress Syndrome). She expired this morning.
A residential house was collapsed due to landslide at Humhama New Airport on Wednesday. Rising kashmir/Farooq Shah

status_message:
CM orders state flag be displayed alongside national flag
RK News
Srinagar: The state government Wednesday directed that all the buildings housing the constitutional Institutions and the official vehicles of Constitutional Authorities should display the state flag alongside the Union flag.
In an order issued today by Commissioner Secretary, General Administration Department, M A Bukhari, it has been ordered that the violation of the government directive will be treated as insult to Jammu and Kashmir prevention of insult to state honors act, 1979. The GAD is headed by chief minister, Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, himself.
“As per the constitution of Jammu and Kashmir and the Delhi Agreement of 1952 and keeping in view the historical background, the state flag has the same sanctity and position as the Union flag has under the Indian constitution and other statutory provisions. Therefore, this sanctity and position has to be maintained at all costs,” read the state government order.
The government order further read that the non-hoisting of the state flag with the Union flag amounts to the insult to the flag as per the provisions of the Jammu and Kashmir Prevention of Insult to State Honors Act 1979.

20 thousand youth appear in a day long Army recruitment drive 
Irfan Raina
Srinagar: Thousands of youth Thursday thronged the JAKLI headquarters at Rangreth Srinagar for a recruitment drive by Army. 
Eyewitness said that more than 2O thousand youth from different areas of Kashmir thronged the venue, since early morning today. They said it was tough for Army to control the crowd, adding that Kashmir Police was called in to handle the situation. 
Sources said that Army has to fill 55 posts of soldiers in JAKLI for which physical test of the candidates were conducted today.

status_message:
CM greets Rising Kashmir on completing 7 yrs in media   
RK News
Jammu: Chief Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed Tuesday greeted English daily newspaper, Rising Kashmir, on completing seven years in publication. The newspaper was launched on March 10, 2008.
In his message, the Chief Minister credited the newspaper for its professionalism in tackling political, economic and social issues that confront the society and playing its role of strengthening the institution of Fourth Estate admirably.  
“Media wields enough influence in society and I hope that newspapers like Rising Kashmir will continue to raise the bar and come up to the expectations of its readers,” he added.

status_message:
Abdul Basit calls on Geelani in Delhi
Agencies
New Delhi: Pakistan envoy Abdul Basit today met Syed Ali Shah Geelani at his residence in Delhi. The two met for about 30 minutes this afternoon and discussed the foreign secretary's visit to Islamabad as well as the situation in Jammu and Kashmir, where a political row has erupted over the release of Masarat Alam.
Jaishankar's visit to Islamabad last Tuesday, as part of a SAARC yatra at Prime Minister Narendra Modi's instance, was seen as a breakthrough after months of cold vibes. Jaishankar and his Pakistani counterpart Aizaz Ahmad Chaudhry had discussed ways to resume the stalled dialogue process, reports said.
India had called off foreign secretary level talks in August last year over the Pakistani envoy's meetings with separatists.

England knocked out of CWC 2015
Agencies
Adelaide: Bangladesh knocked England out of the World Cup with a sensational 15-run Pool A victory at the Adelaide Oval on Monday to make the quarter-finals. Set 276 to win, England were bowled out for 260 despite Jos Buttler's 52-ball 65, while Rubel Hossain claimed 4-53.
Bangladesh had earlier posted 275-7 in Adelaide thanks to 103 from Mahmudullah and Mushfiqur Rahim's 89.
England go out in the first round for the third time in five World Cups, while Bangladesh advance past the first round for only the second occasion.
Bangladesh's victory also secured Sri Lanka's place in the last eight, alongside Pool A winners New Zealand and Australia.
England, meanwhile, face a dead rubber against Afghanistan in Sydney on Friday.
A fourth England defeat in five games is the latest episode in 23 years of World Cup failure and the continuation of a horrendous 18 months in all formats.

status_message:
Centre not consulted on release of Masarat Alam: Modi 
RK News
New Delhi: Prime Minister Narendra Modi today said in Parliament that the release from prison of separatist leader Masarat Alam was unacceptable and that the decision was taken without the Centre's consent.
"I also lend my voice to the outrage on the release of the separatist... this is not one party's outrage, it is the nation's outrage," PM Modi said in the Lok Sabha, promising that there will be "no compromise on the integrity of the nation" or public safety and security.
The Jammu and Kashmir government, PM Modi said, had not consulted the Centre on "its activities post government formation," last week.
Earlier, Home Minister Rajnath Singh said that the Centre had asked the Jammu and Kashmir government for a report on the release and was not satisfied with its response. "I assure the House that after the full clarification from the state government, if needed, we will issue the most severe advisory," Singh said, listing charges against Masarat Alam, which, the minister said, include that of sedition.

Mufti chairs first Cabinet meet
RK News
Jammu: Chief Minister, Mufti Mohammad Sayeed today chaired the first meeting of the Cabinet here. The Cabinet decided to constitute a Cabinet sub Committee under the Minister incharge of the Irrigation and Flood Control Department that will visit the affected areas in central, north and south Kashmir and the worst affected areas in Jammu division to assess the immediate long term needs of the affected population.  The committee has also been tasked to interact with the organizations / associations of the affected traders. 
 The other members of the committee include Lal Singh, Haseeb A. Drabu, Syed Mohammad Altaf Bukhari, and Imran Raza Ansari.
 The Cabinet also reviewed the latest status of the spread of H1N1 (Swine flu) and the availability of medicines, protective kits and testing facilities. 
The Cabinet also reviewed the weather situation across the State and the impact of the bad weather on public services, issuing instructions for the immediate restoration of all the affected services, including roads, power supply, the availability of drinking water and communications.

AIIMS to be set up in Pulwama, IIM in Jmu
RK News
New Delhi: Finance Minister Arun Jaitley Saturday announced that the government would set up branches of AIIMS or the All India Institute of Medical Sciences in five states, including Jammu and Kashmir.

Currently only Delhi has an AIIMS hospital – which is one of the country’s premier research and referral hospitals – and it caters to thousands of patients who come from all over the country.

Jaitley also announced more IITs and IIMs, which are counted among the world’s top engineering and management institutes.

Another Indian Institutes of Technology or IIT will be set up in Karnataka and Indian Institutes of Management (IIMs) will be set up in Jammu and Kashmir and Andhra Pradesh.

Jaitley was presenting union budget 2015 in the parliament. According to sources AIIMS would be established in south Kashmir while as IIM would be established in Jammu.

Reacting to the announcement former chief minister, Omar Abdullah immediately tweeted. “Bricks & mortar don’t make AIIMS & IIMs. In fact quite the opposite, they dilute the brand equity of the original institution,” Omar Tweeted.

Mufti meets Modi 
RK News
New Delhi: New Delhi:  Mufti Mohammad Sayeed, the patron of the People's Democratic Party met Prime Minister Narendra Modi this morning, days after their parties finalised an alliance to form a government in Jammu and Kashmir.
Sayeed, who is set to become the Chief Minister, is expected to formally invite the Prime Minister to his oath ceremony on Sunday.
The BJP is expected to get the deputy chief minister's post.
"We will discuss the Common Minimum Programme tomorrow," Sayeed told reporters in Delhi on Thursday. But he refused to discuss the issues, saying people would see the results.
The alliance between the two parties announced on Tuesday, had faced a last-minute hitch, which was sorted out at a meeting late on Wednesday night. For a time, there were apprehensions that both the meeting between PM Modi and Sayeed and the oath ceremony, might have to be postponed, sources said.
Talking to reporters, Mufti Sayeed said it was important for PM Modi to realise that this was a "great opportunity" to further the peace process in Jammu and Kashmir and build on the legacy of BJP's iconic leader Atal Bihari Vajpayee.
The two parties have agreed to maintain the state's constitutional status - a key demand of Mufti. On the Armed Forces' Special Powers' Act or AFPSA, which gives the army the authority to make arrests without warrants, the two parties have agreed to the gradual replacement of the military with the local police and paramilitary forces in areas where the security situation has improved, reports said.
Sayeed is likely to invite Modi for the function at Jammu’s Zorawar auditorium.

status_message:
DAK sets up swine flu helpline
Issues advisory on vaccination
RK News
Srinagar: Doctors Association Kashmir (DAK) Friday in a statement said that in view of swine flu (H1N1) outbreak in the valley and with no let up in the impact of virus, DAK has set up round the clock helpline numbers for public awareness.
People can call and get information on following phone numbers:
09697988866, 09419409866, 09086889191, 09906832097, 09796337171, 09596251400 and 09469154840.
Communicators on these helpline numbers are expert doctors and will address public concerns on swine flu from today.
People can seek advice on symptoms, prevention, treatment, testing and vaccination.
President DAK and H1N1 expert Dr Nisar ul Hassan said that effective communication to public in an outbreak is vital to prevent the spread of disease and is an intervention in its own right.
Public during an outbreak is entitled to credible and consistent information to build trust which is critical for hastening containment of outbreak.
DAK helpline numbers will address public anxiety and panic created by distrust of health officials who concealed information and failed to protect public health.
Vaccination against H1N1 virus has to be prioritized for high risk persons like pregnant women, persons who live with or care for children younger than 06 months, diabetics, chronic lung or kidney disease, asthmatics, children below 5 years, elderly and health care workers.
Once the demand for vaccine for these target groups is met then everybody should begin vaccinating.
Children younger than 10 years should receive 2 doses of H1N1 vaccine separated by 4 weeks.
Infants younger than 6 months are too young to get any influenza vaccine.

status_message:
PM Modi speaks to Nawaz Sharif
RK News
Srinagar: In a major development Prime Minister Narendra Modi on Friday called his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif. Prime Minister Narendra Modi tweeted this morning that he has spoken to Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif and the heads of other SAARC countries whose teams are playing in the World Cup to wish them luck.
"Spoke to President @ashrafghani, PM Sheikh Hasina, PM Nawaz Sharif & President Sirisena. Conveyed my best wishes for the Cricket World Cup," Modi tweeted.
India take on Pakistan in its first cricket World Cup match in Adelaide on Sunday.
Modi spoke to the Pakistan PM hours after US President Barrack Obama had called Mr Sharif.
Today, he also tweeted, "5 SAARC Nations are playing & are excited about the World Cup. Am sure WC will celebrate sportsman spirit & will be a treat for sports lovers...Cricket connects people in our region & promotes goodwill. Hope players from SAARC region play with passion & bring laurels to the region."
He also said that India's new Foreign Secretary S Jaishankar would embark "on a SAARC Yatra soon to further strengthen our ties."
The GoI had cancelled the foreign secretary-level talks with Pakistan scheduled last year after Islamabad refused to agree to India's demand of not entertaining Hurriyat leaders.

Man allegedly dies in Police custody 
RK News
Srinagar: Scores of people took to streets Wednesday in Kupwara against the death of a man allegedly killed in police custody in Kupwara district of north Kashmir. According to reports, the youth Nazir Ahmad Mughal of Zirhama was arrested by police few days back in connection with a case.
Locals alleged that today morning Nazir was brought dead to the Sub-District hospital Kupwara. They alleged that he was killed in custody. A senior doctor of the hospital said that Nazir was brought dead this morning.
However, Police spokesman said, that Nazir Ahmad Mughal of Zirhama, Kupwara who was in police custody complained of chest pain and was shifted to District Hospital Kupwara for treatment. He was attended by Dist hospital doctors and after few hours he gave slip to police in the garb of attending the call of nature. Instantly the search was conducted to trace him out. status_message:
Kashmiri exporter in HSBC’s ‘Swiss Leak’ List
RK News
Srinagar: A prominent exporter of Kashmiri carpets and pashmina shawls is listed among prominent people who are on the HSBC list, reports The Indian Express.
Haseeb Shaw, whose father is a joint account-holder and they had a $2.13-million maximum balance in 2006-07, the daily reported.
According to the report, Shaw is Managing Director of the Srinagar-based Cottage Arts Emporium, which also has a branch in New Delhi.
HSBC data shows he opened his account in 1997. He is listed as one who does commerce in carpets and textiles. His father, the report says, Shaw Abdul Rashid, is a joint account-holder and they had a $2.13-million maximum balance in 2006-07.
Several meetings between HSBC bankers and the two account-holders are listed — they asked for a second safe deposit box abroad and are noted as emptying out one which was stuffed with pashmina shawls.
Several top businessmen listed include Mukesh Ambani, Anil Ambani, Anand Chand Burman, Rajan Nanda, Yashovardhan Birla, Chandru Lachhmandas Raheja, Dattaraj Salgaocar, Bhadrashyam Kothari and Shravan Gupta.

Guru's hanging wrong, badly handled: Tharoor
Agencies
New Delhi: Congress leader Shashi Tharoor Monday said that the hanging of Parliament attack convict Afzal Guru in 2013 was “wrong and badly handled,” potentially embarrassing his own party, which was in power at the time.
“I think the hanging was both wrong and badly handled. Family should have been warned, given a last meeting and body returned,” Tharoor, tweeted. 
The comments follow revelations that five Congress lawmakers in Jammu and Kashmir admitted in a signed statement that Afzal Guru's hanging was a “mistake.”

status_message:
Pak targets villages, 8 BoPs with mortar bombs, one injured
PTI
Jammu: Pakistani Rangers indulged in heavy firing and mortar shelling overnight on eight border outposts and some villages along the international border in Jammu district, leaving one person injured.
“Pakistani Rangers resorted to small arms firing and mortar shelling along IB in R.S. Pura sector of Jammu district since 2200 hours last night,” a BSF official said on Monday.
They targeted eight border outposts (BoPs) and some civilian areas he said adding that Pakistani Rangers also fired 81 mm mortar shells.
In the firing, Khadim Hussain in Jora Farm village suffered minor splinter injuries, a police officer said.
BSF troops guarding the border line retaliated effectively and the firing exchange continued till 0100 hours today, PRO said.
There have been three ceasefire violations along IB in Samba, Arnia and R S Pura in February this year.
In January this year, Pakistan resorted to several ceasefire violations resulting in death of four people and injuries to seven people.

Kashmir shuts on Guru's anniversary
RK News
Srinagar: Strict restrictions have been imposed in parts of Srinagar city on second death anniversary of Afzal Guru who was hanged in Tihar jail in 2013.
Heavy deplyoment of paramilitary forces can be seen in parts of Kashmir, mostly in sensitive areas like the old city in Srinagar as well as Sopore which is the hometown of Guru.
Guru who belonged to Sopore area of Baramulla district was given death sentence for his alleged role in the December 2001 attack on the Indian Parliament.
Shops, business establishments and fuel stations are also closed. The roads in Lal Chowk area wore a deserted look as public transport is off the roads.

status_message:
Delhi records 63.46% voter turnout till 5
Agencies
New Delhi: While North East Delhi reported the highest voter turnout of 66.37 per cent, the lowest was in South Delhi with 61.7 per cent, according to the Delhi Election Commission.
Central Delhi recorded 64.66 per cent turnout, East Delhi 64.67 per cent, New Delhi 59.29 per cent and North Delhi registered a turnout of 65.56 per cent.
While North East Delhi reported the highest voter turnout of 66.37 per cent, the lowest was in South Delhi with 61.7 per cent, according to the Delhi Election Commission.
Central Delhi recorded 64.66 per cent turnout, East Delhi 64.67 per cent, New Delhi 59.29 per cent and North Delhi registered a turnout of 65.56 per cent.
The Delhi polls are seen as a direct contest between AAP and BJP. This is the second assembly polls in Delhi within little over one year. The assembly polls in December 2013 had thrown a hung verdict with BJP winning 31 seats and AAP making a stunning debut by wresting 28 seats while Congress got only 8 in the 70-member assembly.

“Muslims should marry more than once have more children” Separatist leader
RK News
Srinagar: A hard-line separatist leader Mohammad Qasim Faktoo today asked Kashmiri Muslims to have more wives and produce more children to fight what he called a “conspiracy to change demography of state”.
In a statement, Faktoo who complete 22 years in jail on February 5 for his alleged involvement in number of militant related violent cases gave a detailed account of how “Islam allows this” He called on Imams of mosques to spread this message.  ”We request  local  mosque  imams to make people  aware  about  the importance of having more  children.  Further  we request  doctors  not  to do  unnecessary  birth  control  surgeries  without an excuse valid  under  Shariah. We appeal  well  to do Muslims to marry  more  than  once and have as many  children  as possible. The Quranic  tenet  of justice  between  wives  is  only  in providing  equal  provision  and not inclination of the heart’ said Faktoo who heads Muslim Deeni Mahaz (Muslim Religious Front)
It is pertinent to mention that Faktoo is married to Asiya Andrabi, head of right wing women’s outfit Dukhtaran-e- Milat (Daughters of Nation)

LoC trade suspended 
Junaid Kathju
Srinagar: A day after Jammu and Kashmir Police  police seized a truck carrying around 10 kilograms of  narcotic substances coming from Muzafarabad, the authorities on either side today suspended the cross Line of Control (LoC) trade.

It is not known whether the two sides have started negotiations on the issues. Yesterday at least 70 trucks were halted on both sides after the narcotic substance was recovered on this side of Kashmir giving yet another jolt to the trade.

“Not in hurry to form the govt” Mufti
RK News
Jammu : Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) patron and former Chief Minister Mufti Mohammad Sayeed today said that his party was not in hurry to form the government.
After his casting his vote for electing four members for Rajya Sabha (Upper House of parliament) he told reporters “we are not in hurry. Whatever we will do will it for the prosperity of Jammu and Kashmir”. He did not divulge any details.
However, PDP sources have disclosed that formal talks with BJP on government formation will begin on February 11.

“Not allowing Afzal’s family to meet him was a mistake” Cong MLA’s 
Syed Amjad Shah
Jammu : In a last ditch effort to reach out to Independent MLA from Langate Er Rashid five MLA’s of Congress owing their allegiance to Ghulam Nabi Azad led faction, today said that not to allow Afzal Guru’s family to meet him before hanging on February 9 last year was a mistake.
The five MLA’s G M saroori, Vikar Rasool, Haji Rashid, Mohammad Amin Bhat and Gulzar Wani in a desperate bid to see that Azad sails through the crucial election for Rajya Sabha held today said in a signed statement that they echoed Rashid’s demand for returns the mortal remains of Afzal to his family. Rashid did vote but it will be clear only when results out that for whom he voted. Congress has 12 members in assembly but only five have signed the appeal.
The MLA’s also assailed PDP on a statement issued regarding Afzal Guru yesterday. “The demand made by Rashid for return of his mortal remains is a humanitarian issue” they said adding “the views of Er Rashid regarding allowing a last meeting to his kith and kin of Afzal Guru are genuine and based on humanitarian values and same was a mistake”. It was Congress led UPA government that hanged Guru last year picking him from the 28th number of the list of those on death row.

83 votes polled for Rajya Sahba election in JK
RK News
Jammu: The voting for Rajya Sabha Elelction was held today to decide the prospects of seven candidates including former chief minister and leader of opposition in Rajya Sahba Ghulam Nabi Azad.
The voting which started early in morning was continuing till reports last came in. By now 83 votes were polled by the newly elected MLAs.

Delhi polls begin: AAP, BJP in a neck to neck battle
Agencies
New Delhi: Delhi, which is voting for a new government today, has recorded a voter turnout. Arvind Kejriwal's Aam Aadmi Party is locked in a close contest with Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP). 
Kejriwal's morning tweet included a smiley and a pun. "Everyone must please go out and vote after getting ready and offering prayers. Aapki zaroor jeet hogi (AAP/you will definitely win)"
Also an early voter was Kiran Bedi, the BJP's presumptive chief minister, who tweeted as she set out to vote, "The Sun God from my Window. Magnanimous for all, always. Giving me the Energy to Serve...Thank you."  
President Pranab Mukherjee, Vice President Hamid Ansari, Union Minister Harsh Vardhan and Sharmishtha Mukherjee are Congress candidate from Greater Kailash and the President's daughter, were among other early voters.
The AAP, which had put up a stellar performance in the December 2013 assembly polls, seemed confident about its chances. "We expect to win more than 47 seats," said AAP leader Yogendra Yadav.
Results will be announced on Tuesday.

status_message:
Pak wants normal relations with India on basis of mutual respect: Nawaz Sharif         
RK News
Islamabad: Pakistan's High Commissioner to India, Abdul Basit called on Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif at PM House on Wednesday and briefed him on the status of Pakistan-India relations.
The Pakistan Prime Minister reiterated that the country wants good neighborly relations with all countries of the region.

Nawaz said India is an important neighbor for us and we would like to have normal relations with the country on basis of mutual respect and sovereign equality.

Pakistan premier also said, “It is important that two countries resolve all their outstanding issues including Jammu and Kashmir in order to have viable peace in the region.”

status_message:
R.K. Laxman passes away
RK News
Pune: Legendry cartoonist and creator of the ‘Common Man’, R.K. Laxman, (93) passed away at the Deenanath Mangeshkar hospital in Pune on Monday evening. 
Laxman was hospitalized earlier this month for a urinary infection. He was put on ventilator support after multi-organ failure. He had reportedly suffered several strokes since 2010.
His work, spanning over six decades, chronicled the fortunes and foibles of Independent India.
Through his iconic character of "The Common Man", Laxman targeted politicians with sly humour.
He was best known for fearlessly lampooning political leaders from Jawaharlal Nehru to Atal Behari Vajpayee. He spared no one, not even Indira Gandhi during the Emergency.
He won many prestigious awards including the Magsaysay and state awards like the Padma Bhushan and Padma Vibhushan. Yet he remained fiercely critical of the political class.
Indian and Pakistani army Monday exchanged greetings and sweets on the line of control (LoC) at Aman Kaman Seetu post (Peace Bridge) to mark India’s republic Day. Risning Kashmir/Tajamul Islam

Hundreds join peaceful Je suis Muslim rally in Sydney
Agencies
Sydney: Hundreds of Muslims rallied in Sydney on Friday night to protest negative media coverage of Islam and the French magazine Charlie Hebdo’s depictions of the Prophet Mohammed (PBUH).
Protesters held placards with the slogan Je suis Muslim, French for “I am Muslim.”
Organisers of the “Our Prophet, Our Honour” rally said it was intended to be “a peaceful and respectful event” to counter negative media coverage of Islam and Charlie Hebdo’s lampooning of their Prophet.

status_message:
Man alleges RDD official demanding bribe
Sheikh Saleem
Bandipora: A beneficiary of Indira Awas Yojna (IAY) has filed a complaint against officials of Rural Development Department for demanding bribe against grant of money under the scheme.
Earlier BDO office had lodged FIR against Public Relations Officer (PRO) and nephew of former legislator Nizamudin Bhat, Inam ul Haq Bhat, for allegedly attacking officials of Rural Development Department.
Bhat rejected the claims of RDD officials and alleged that the officials were demanding bribe from the beneficiary. “When I went to inquire about the delay of the application, the officials got furious and entered into verbal argument with me,” he alleged.
Gulzar Ahmad of Sonarwani Bandipora has complained against Statistical Officer in BDO’s Office for demanding bribe. SHO Bandipora while confirming the counter complaint by beneficiary said they will investigate the matter.

Central Reserve Police Force (CRPF) men stand guard outside Bakhshi Stadium, the main venue for the Republic Day celebrations in Srinagar on Saturday, 24 January 2015. Security has been beefed up in Kashmir ahead of Republic Day celebrations on 26. Rising Kashmir/Farooq Javed

status_message:
RK reporter wins gender sensitivity award
RK News
Srinagar: Rising Kashmir reporter, Sumaiya Yousuf declared winner of the Laadli Media Award for Gender Sensitivity from the northern region of India. Sumaiya would be felicitated with the award at Raipur in Chattisgarh next month.  
The prestigious Laadli Media and Advertising Awards for Gender Sensitivity (Northern and Western Region), aims to popularise gender-sensitive reporting and advertising in the country. 
Launched in March 2007 in Mumbai, the focus of the awards is on mainstreaming gender into media and promoting gender sensitivity as a core value in reporting and programming.

Mehbooba Mufti re-elected PDP president
RK News
Srinagar: Peoples Democratic Party Saturday re-elected incumbent party chief Mehbooba Mufti as its president for the fifth time after she won the elections unopposed.
52-year-old Mehbooba, a law graduate from the University of Kashmir, joined politics in 1996 when she was elected from Bijbehara Assembly seat on Congress ticket.

RK News
Srinagar : The Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) will field Fayaz Ahmad Mir and Nazir Ahmad Laway for two Rajya Sabha seats for which elections are scheduled to be held on February 7.

Sources told Rising Kashmir that names of Mir and Laway who lost the recent Assembly elections with thin margin from Kupwara and Kulgam respectively have been finalized by the party leadership.

status_message:
King Abdullah dies, Prince Salman assumes Saudi throne
Agencies
Riyadh: Saudi King Abdullah bin Abdulaziz has died in hospital, royal officials have announced.
A statement, made early on Friday, said his brother, Salman, had become king.
King Abdullah, who was said to be aged about 90, had been in hospital for several weeks suffering from a lung infection.
Abdullah came to the throne in 2005 but had suffered
frequent bouts of ill health in recent years.

status_message:
Not scared of Pakistan’s threat: Rajnath Singh
PTI
New Delhi: With Intelligence reports suggesting Pakistan-based militants planning strikes in India, Home Minister Rajnath Singh Saturday said Pakistan is “not mending its ways” despite being given a befitting reply many times.
“Pakistan is not mending its ways. Despite getting a befitting reply many times, it is not mending its ways. But India is not scared of Pakistan’s threat,” he told PTI here.
He was replying to a question on Intelligence inputs which said strikes could be carried out by militant groups on “soft targets” in Jammu and Kashmir ahead of U.S. President Barack Obama’s visit to India this month.
Singh, however, said no effort will be left to foil any such attempts by militants to disturb peace.
“For security, whatever necessary steps are required, we will take,” he said.

MLA's driver, Zahoor Ahmad Dar, was also injured in the firing and unconfirmed reports said that Dar has succumbed to his injuries.

status_message:
Police foils JKLF’s protest march 
Junaid Kathju
Srinagar: Police Friday foiled protest march of Jammu and Kashmir Liberation Front (JKLF) against settling of West Pakistan Refugee and detained its chairman Mohammad Yasin Malik along with his supporters.
Malik led the protest march of JKLF activists from party headquarters at Maisuma towards Lal Chowk. Carrying placards and banners, the JKLF activists were chanting anti-India and pro-freedom slogans. 
Police and CRPF men, who were deployed in strength in the area, intercepted the procession and resorted to heavy tear smoke shelling and Lathi charge to quell the protests. 
Association of Parents of Disappeared Persons (APDP) chairperson Parveena Ahangar who was accompanying Malik during the march fell unconscious because of heavy tear smoke, was shifted to hospital.

status_message:
NC leader ‘manhandles’ official
Shah Suhail
Anantnag: A senior National Conference (NC) leader Thursday allegedly manhandled the Assistant Deputy Commissioner (ADC), Anantnag, blaming the district administration of disparity in distribution of relief to the flood victims.
The employees at the Deputy Commissioner's office have stopped working and are out protesting against the high handedness of the politician.
They said that the NC leader Bashir Ahmad Veeri, who unsuccessfully contested the recently contested assembly polls from Bijbehara, barged into the ACD's office and after a heated exchange of words manhandled the officer.
The employees are demanding that an FIR be lodged against the erring leader.
Veeri meanwhile refused allegations of man handling the official.
"There was a heated exchange of words after the official in question spoke ill of me and one of my colleagues."

Peace in Kashmir has to be maintained: Army chief
PTI
New Delhi: The hard-fought peace in militancy-hit Jammu and Kashmir has to be maintained, Army chief Dalbir Singh Suhag Thursday said as he accused Pakistan of supporting militancy in the state.
He also said that the Army needs to focus on war preparation which is its “primary task.”
“The peace in Jammu and Kashmir, which was brought with great difficulty, has to be maintained,” Gen. Suhag said while addressing his force on the occasion of 67th Army Day.
He said the recent attacks show that militants continue to get support from “across the border.”
Earlier this week too, he had accused Pakistan of continuing to support “proxy war” in Jammu and Kashmir despite suffering casualties due to terror on its soil.

Shopian encounter ends, 5 militants killed 
RK News
Srinagar: At least five militants were killed by the forces after a fierce gunfight in south Kashmir's Shopian district Thursday afternoon.
The gun-battle began after an Army search party was targeted by the militants hiding in Kaddar forest of Shopian area this morning.
Today's operation comes a day after a militant was killed by the forces in Sopore.

Encounter in Shopian between militants and forces
RK News
Srinagar: A gunfight erupted between militants and forces in Shopian Thursday morning.
Reports said that Army’s 44RR, SOG and 183 BN CRPF cordoned off the Kharot area of Shopian today morning.
As the forces intensified the search in the area, the militant’s believed to be three to four in number opened fire. The joint team of forces retaliated ensuing in a fierce encounter.
So far three militants have been killed and the encounter is still going on.

Our offer to PDP for Outside Support, not to join government: NC
RK News
Srinagar: National Conference Wednesday said that it should be amply clear that NC's offer to PDP was an offer of Outside Support for PDP to form the Government in JK and that National Conference was not interested in being a part of such a Government with PDP in the State. 
Terming PDP Chief Spokesperson Naeem Akhtar's remarks as misinformed and unfounded, National Conference General Secretary Ali Mohammad Sagar said that unlike PDP, National Conference has put its ideology and the State's Special Status above the petty trappings of power by not aligning with BJP. 
NC also rubbished PDP's deluded claim that National Conference had been punished or sidelined by the people.
Army soldiers take position during a gunfight in which one militant was killed in Chankhan area of Sopore on Wednesday, January 14, 2015.Rising Kashmir/Tajamul Islam

PDP appears disinclined to accept NC offer
PTI
Srinagar: Peoples Democratic Party (PDP), Wednesday indicated that it may not be inclined to accept National Conference’s offer of support for forming a government.
“The people have voted against the National Conference in the elections and with just 15 seats, they (NC) cannot decide on the government formation,” PDP Chief spokesperson Naeem Akhtar told PTI here.
Akhtar was commenting on the letter sent by NC’s working president Omar Abdullah to Governor N.N. Vohra on Tuesday to inform him about his party’s support to the PDP and asking him not to take any decision on government formation without consulting his party.
PDP and BJP have been in talks but failed to reach any agreement even three weeks after the results came, following which the Governor’s Rule was imposed in the state last week.

Former Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister Omar Abdullah accused PDP’s patron Mufti Mohammed Sayeed of continuing the deadlock over government formation to get a full six-year term as Chief Minister.
“It’s been months since the state had a full fledged administration and the people can’t wait for Mufti Sayeed to negotiate his six-year term,” Omar tweeted after the state was put under Governor’s rule.
Peoples Democratic Party, which has not been able to cobble an alliance for government formation in Jammu and Kashmir, today blamed former Chief Minister Omar Abdullah for forcing Governor’s Rule on the state.
“We had time till January 19 to form a government but the situation has been forced (on the state) by Omar,” PDP chief spokesman Naeem Akhtar said.

Vohra had recommended the direct rule to centre yesterday after Omar Abdullah declined to continue as care taker Chief Minister. The union government is understood to have given its nod to the Governor's rule which has come into effect after the approval of President of India.

status_message:
Omar decides to step down as caretaker JK chief minister
RK News
Srinagar: Omar Abdullah Thursday decided not to continue as caretaker Chief Minister of Jammu and Kashmir, arguing that the state needed a full-time administrator.
Omar met Governor NN Vohra in Delhi last night soon after his return from London after visiting his ailing parents and is understood have conveyed that he wished to be relieved of the position of caretaker chief minister.
 “Just to confirm I did meet Gov Vohra sahib last night & ask him to relieve me as caretaker CM. I had agreed to stay temporarily,” Omar tweeted. 
He was asked to continue as caretaker chief minister on December 24 after his resignation in the wake of defeat of his party, National Conference (NC), in the Assembly poll on December 23. 
The new government is required to be constituted before January 19 when the term of the current Assembly expires failing which Governor's rule looks inevitable. Omar's decision means such a rule may have to be imposed earlier.
Omar has already put the onus on his arch-rival PDP for pushing the state to a Constitutional crisis. "I don't envy the @jkpdp having to explain the imminent imposition of central rule when they've had a credible offer of support from @JKNC," Omar tweeted.

Efforts to improve ties with India not reciprocated: Nawaz Sharief
Agencies
Manama: Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif Thursday said that his government made sincere efforts to improve relations with the government of India, but the efforts were not reciprocated. 
Addressing a gathering of overseas Pakistanis in Bahrain, Nawaz Sharif said India cancelled the foreign secretary level talks with Pakistan on the pretext of the Pakistani High Commissioner's meeting with the Kashmir leadership, which has been a practice for 60 years.
He underscored that Pakistan desires to have good relations with all the neighbours.

More attacks in Paris, two police officers shot, explosion at restaurant near a mosque

In another incident an explosion was heard from a restaurant next to a mosque in Lyon, reports said. No injuries have been reported in the blast. The attacks come barely a day after the 12 people were massacred at Charle Hebdo magazine's office in Paris.
The gunman who attacked on the policemen fled by the metro after the incident. A suspect has since been detained in connection with the shootout and is being questioned. The incident took place near Porte de Chatillon south of Paris.

Pak restricts bus service from India to Wagah
PTI
Lahore: For the first time since the Pak-India Dosti bus service was launched between New Delhi and Lahore, Pakistan has restricted its entry here and Nankana Sahib city, citing increased “terror threats.”
The Pakistan Tourism Development Corporation has said the Pak-India Dosti bus service will now on be operated only up to Wagah Border.
“The PTDC has shifted the entire bus operation at its sub-office at Wagah. Passengers leaving for New Delhi and Amritsar from here will now have to catch the bus at Wagah.
Similarly, those arriving here from across the border by the service will disembark at Wagah too,” an official of PTDC told PTI.
He said the decision has been taken in the wake of growing terror threats.
Earlier, police used to escort the buses from Wagah to Lahore’s Gulberg and Nankana Sahib terminals. Similarly, the police used to provide escort to the Dosti buses from Gulberg and Nankana Sahib to Wagah.
The bus service between the two countries was started on March 16, 1999 primarily to enhance people-to-people contact.

BSF foils infiltration bid in Kathua district of JK

Jammu: The Border Security Force Wednesday foiled a bid by Pakistan-based militants to infiltrate into Jammu and Kashmir under the cover of firing from across the border and thick fog in Kathua district of Jammu and Kashmir.
“There was movement of a group of militants along international border in Pallia area in Chilyari-khora forward belt in Kathua district last night,” a senior BSF officer said on Wednesday.
Alert BSF troops opened fire foiling the infiltration bid, he said.
This is the fifth infiltration attempt in a week by militants under the cover of firing by Pakistani troops and thick blanket of fog along the international border.
Director General of BSF D.K. Pathak on Tuesday visited border areas in Samba and Kathua to assess the situation.

Sopore: Complete shutdown is being observed in Sopore town, Baramulla district to mark the anniversary of Sopore massacre of January 06, 1993.
At least 56 people were killed in BSF firing on this day in 1993. More than 300 shops and other business establishments were also burnt in the town.
Shops and other business establishments in the township are closed today. Police and paramilitary forces were seen patrolling in numbers. 
After 22 years, the victim families are still awaiting justice while the guilty according to the victims are roaming free.

Border shelling continues
Agencies
Jammu: Pakistani troops continued to fire across the border in Jammu and Kashmir overnight, targeting several Border Security Force or BSF posts. 
The heavy shelling has forced nearly 10,000 people living close to the border to flee their homes. Schools and colleges are indefinitely closed and even relief camps have had to be evacuated in some areas, with the shelling over the last few days extending to as much as 3.5 km inside the Indian territory in some places like Chakra, Sherpur and Londi. 
Ongoing examinations for Class XI have been put off.
Yesterday, 15 Indian posts were attacked by the Pakistan Rangers in Samba and Hiranagar. One BSF jawan was injured and later died. The Director General of the BSF is scheduled to go to Jammu today and visit the forward areas.
One woman was killed and 10 other civilians injured in ceasefire violations earlier this week.

Wait for two days, you will come to know about CM candidate: Jugal Kishore
Agencies
New Delhi: The Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) leaders from J&K met party chief Amit Shah in Delhi on Monday to discuss the strategy for talks on forming government in JK. 
After meeting Shah, BJP leader Ram Madhav said that there has been some forward movement in the talks and the Peoples Democratic Party, is in touch with them. BJP leaders, however, claimed that the party will be a part of the government formation in the state.
"The BJP will be part of the government. It is up to Amit Shah to decide on alliance partners," Party leader Jugal Kishore Sharma said. 
Commenting about chief ministerial candidate he said, "Wait for two days, you will come to know about CM candidate." 
Rejecting reports that her party has started formal talks with the BJP over government formation in the state, Mehbooba Mufti had on Sunday said that no such decision has been taken. Both the BJP and PDP have repeatedly said that they are keeping all their options open.

Amit Shah meets BJP leaders from JK
Agencies
New Delhi: BJP chief Amit Shah has summoned top leaders of his party in Jammu and Kashmir unit for an urgent meeting in Delhi Monday to discuss the way forward in the state.
The meeting in Delhi comes as regional party People's Democratic Party hinted that it could tie up with the BJP. Leaders said the PDP wants development and reconstruction in the state which they do not envisage happening if they partner with rival regional party the National Conference or the Congress.  
But sources say formal talks between the PDP and the BJP scheduled for tomorrow may be delayed after fresh border tension with Pakistan. One of the conditions that the PDP has reportedly set for an alliance with the BJP is that the Centre resume talks with Pakistan.
There are other demands that the PDP has reportedly made. It wants the revocation of the Armed Forces (Special Powers) Act or AFSPA, talks to be held with Kashmiri separatists and the promise that Article 370, which grants special status to J&K will not be revoked. These are issues that the BJP has held an opposite stance on for years.  
 "We don't want to take any decision in haste, we want an alliance which will be stable for six years," said the BJP's state president Jugal Kishore, in Delhi. "All options are open and a decision will be taken soon," he added.
The two parties have also been exploring tie-ups with other parties to make up the numbers for a majority at 44 seats.
Amit Shah Friday said, "Talks are on with both parties (PDP and NC). There has been no fruitful outcome (yet)."
The Governor has set January 19 as a deadline for government formation in the state.

"So when I raised AFSPA I was accused of playing politics with Nat Sec (national security). BJP negotiates Govt (government) formation with @jkpdp using AFSPA & that's OK??" Omar wrote on micro-blogging site Twitter.
Omar also criticized Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) for its "assertion" that a coalition with BJP is necessary for getting the special assistance of Rs 44,000 crore submitted by his government for the flood-affected people of the state.
"We are being told by the @jkpdp that the tie up with BJP is necessary for the 44,000 Cr flood relief. Shouldn't a state just get its due?" Omar said.

“Pakistani Rangers resorted to ceasefire violation and opened small arms firing in one post in Samba district and two areas in Kathua district late last night,” officials said told PTI.
There was firing on Bobiyan and Pansar forward areas along International Border (IB) in Kathua district since last night, Deputy Commissioner (Kathua) Shahid Iqbal Choudhary said, adding it was going on intermittently.
In Samba district, there were two rounds of small arms firing on Ballard post in Ramgarh sub-sector last night, SSP (Samba) Anil Magotra said, adding that by and large there was calm along IB in Samba.
There was no loss of life or injury to anyone.
However, residents of border villages continue to leave for safer areas in view of the latest round of ceasefire violations by Pakistan since New Year eve.
Over 3,500 people have migrated from border villages in Samba and Kathua districts.

Pakistan Foreign Office spokesperson Tasneem Aslam denied that any boat from Keti Bunder port of the country's Sindh province had sailed off.
Sources in the foreign office termed the Indian claim as mere propaganda to tarnish the image of Pakistan, the report added.
On Friday, the Indian officials said that a suspicious Pakistani fishing boat apparently loaded with explosives blew up in the sea and sank off Gujarat after being intercepted by the Indian Coast Guard.
The Coast Guard has increased surveillance along the Gujarat coast, after a Pakistani boat blew itself off Porbandar on New Year's Eve.
"The entire Gujarat Coast is under surveillance, six-seven aircraft are continuously monitoring it and we are also vigilant," Coast Guard Inspector General Kuldeep Singh Sheoran said today.

Heavy firing by Pakistan at International Border in JK
PTI
Jammu: The latest round of ceasefire violations by Pakistan which started on New Year eve has left a Border Security Force (BSF) trooper dead and seven others injured while five Pakistani Rangers have been killed in retaliatory firing by India. 
"Pakistani troops resorted to unprovoked and heavy firing and mortar shelling on posts and civilian areas along IB in Samba and Kathua districts since 2130 hours last night," Inspector General of BSF Rakesh Sharma told PTI.
"BSF troops gave a befitting reply resulting in exchanges which stopped at 3 AM in the morning," the IG said, adding that Pakistan again started mortar shelling and firing targeting civilian areas since 7 AM and it is going on intermittently.
He said that all border outposts in three battalion areas of Samba and Hiranagar sub-sectors in Kathua district were targeted.
Four persons, including two women, were injured in Nauchak village in Kathua while 300 people have been shifted, officials said.
Two persons were injured in Baingallar border hamlet in Samba, Senior Superintendent of Police (SSP), Samba, Anil Magotra told PTI, adding that firing exchanges were going on intermittently.
The injured have been shifted to hospital, he said.
Last night, the force had thwarted a "major infiltration attempt" from across the border.
Under the cover of shelling and firing, the Rangers tried to push a group of seven to eight heavily armed militants from forward area of Chor Gali in Samba sector at 11.30 PM.

Pak court stops execution of death row convict
PTI
Islamabad: A Pakistani court today ordered the authorities to stop the execution of a death row convict involved in the killing of a soldier in 2000.
Lahore High Court’s two-member bench headed by Justice Abdus Sami Khan halted the execution on the petition filed by the counsel of the convict Faiz Ahmad.
Ahmad’s counsel Abdul Khaliq told the court that his client’s appeal against the death sentence had been pending in the Supreme Court since 2009 and requested to set aside the death warrant.

The Home Minister said Pakistan has been firing towards Indian side along the International Border in Jammu region and the BSF was giving a befitting reply.
“BSF jawans are giving a befitting reply,” he said.
When asked about Islamabad’s protest against heavy firing by India, Singh said it was Pakistan which started the firing and “we are just responding to it”.
Pakistan Rangers on Thursday targeted 13 border outposts in Samba sector in Jammu and Kashmir, a day after four Pakistani rangers were killed in a sharp counter-attack following the death of an Indian trooper in cross-border firing.

The fishing vessel was deemed suspicious and then intercepted and chased by the Coast Guard for nearly an hour off the coast of Porbandar. After the Coast Guard fired at the boat to warn it to stop, the vessel blew up.

Judicial appointments commission bill gets President’s nod
PTI
New Delhi: The Constitutional amendment Bill that seeks to scrap the collegium system of appointing judges to higher judiciary has received Presidential nod. The National Judicial Appointments Commission (NJAC) Bill passed by the Parliament in August this year has received President’s assent, official sources said.
The new law facilitates the setting up of a commission for appointment of judges, replacing the 20-year-old collegium system, which has been under severe criticism.
It paves the way for the setting up of NJAC, which will appoint and transfer judges to the Supreme Courts and the 24 High Courts. The Bill, 124th amendment to the Constitution, grants Constitutional status to the NJAC and its composition which will be headed by the Chief Justice of India.
As many as 16 of the 29 states have ratified the Bill. Any Constitutional amendment Bill requires ratification by at least 50 per cent of the state legislatures. Besides the CJI, the judiciary would be represented by two senior judges of the Supreme Court. Two eminent personalities and the Law Minister will be the other members of the body.

Mullah Omar hiding in Pak: Afghan spy chief
PTI
New Delhi: Taliban’s reclusive leader Mullah Muhammad Omar is alive and hiding in the Pakistani city of Karachi, a top Afghan intelligence official has said. 
“There is a lot of doubt whether he is alive or not. But we are more confident that he is in Karachi,” acting Afghan intelligence chief Rahmatullah Nabil was quoted as saying in the New York Times regarding Omar’s whereabouts.
An European official, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said in the NYT report that there is a “consensus among all three branches of the Afghan security forces that Mullah Omar is alive”.
The report said that Mullah Omar has always functioned more as the spiritual and ideological leader of the movement than as an operational commander.
His inner circle, made up of village mullahs who have known one another for decades, has provided the active leadership of the Taliban’s many local factions.
“But now one man, Mullah Akhtar Muhammad Mansour, has risen to the No 2 role and become the main link to Mullah Omar, allowing him to place his loyalists up and down the ranks,” Nabil said in the report.
Nabil, in his assessment, saw Pakistan’s security establishment driving the changes, an appraisal shared by some Western officials.
Other Afghan officials, along with some European and American counterparts, said the suggestions that Mullah Omar had died were a propaganda ploy intended to weaken Taliban morale, not a reflection of the true thinking within the Afghan government.

“Jammu recorded 4.3 as the minimum temperature.”

Search expands for missing AirAsia plane 
Agencies
Jakarta: Search planes and ships from several countries on Monday, were scouring Indonesian waters over which an AirAsia jet carrying 162 people disappeared, and more than a day into the region's latest aviation mystery, officials doubted there could be anything but a tragic ending.
AirAsia Flight vanished Sunday in airspace thick with storm clouds on its way from Surabaya, Indonesia, to Singapore. The search expanded Monday, but has yet to find any trace of the Airbus A320.
First Adm. Sigit Setiayana, the Naval Aviation Center commander at the Surabaya air force base, said 12 navy ships, five planes, three helicopters and a number of warships were taking part in the search, along with ships and planes from Singapore and Malaysia.
The Australian Air Force also sent a search plane. Searchers had to cope with heavy rain Sunday, but Setiayana said Monday that visibility was good.

Regional parties should get united to form next govt: Tarigami    
Junaid Kathju
Srinagar: CPI (M) leader Mohammad Yusuf Tarigami Saturday said by aligning with BJP to form the next government would prove catastrophic for the state of Jammu and Kashmir.
Tarigami said his support would be for any non BJP government. “I will support any regional party who will keep BJP at bay. The communal agendas of BJP is a serious threat to the secularism of the state.” 
Tarigami said all those parties who are holding back channel talks with BJP to form the next government should realize its consequences for future. “A better sense should prevail among the regional parties. I appeal all the regional parties to get united and form the next government on secular grounds,” Tarigami added.

Will take cadre, people on board before any decision: Mehbooba
RK News
Srinagar: Amid growing confusion over formation of coalition, PDP President Mehbooba Mufti today said the party will take not only its cadres but the people of the State on board before arriving on any decision regarding the future course of action.
 
“I want to assure my party cadres and the people that whatever decision is to be taken will be taken in the larger interest of the State and its people,” she said in a statement.
 
She said the mandate given by the people to the PDP to represent the political aspirations and economic interests of all the regions and sub-regions of Jammu and Kashmir would be represented and valued in adequate measure.
 
Mehbooba also said only the PDP Chief Spokesman Naeem Akhtar is authorized to articulate the party’s views in the media on the policy matters, “In the prevailing hazy political scenario, unqualified comments in the media only add to the confusion and fuel wild speculations," she said.

Not first time PDP MLAs have misused security, their guns: NC
RK News
Srinagar: National Conference Friday condemned the incident of newly elected PDP MLA from Sonawar, Mohammad Ashraf Mir resorting to firing an AK-47 amid a crowd and said that such reckless, unlawful behavior from an elected lawmaker was unfortunate and unacceptable, especially in a State that had just recovered from a prolonged phase of armed, violent turmoil. 
"How can an MLA resort to firing a gun in broad daylight? Apparently the gun was handed over to Mir by a personal security officer of the J&K Police. This behavior is shocking and violates a slew of laws, most of which are non-bailable offences. However, this is not the first time Ashraf Mir has misused his personal security. More recently, Mir used his PSOs to conduct illegal search operations and beat up innocent people in Shalimar the night before the elections in Srinagar. However, tragically Mir was allowed to go scot-free that time due to the unabashed bias of a certain police officer towards PDP. Now once again there is video evidence of Mir violating the law  by firing the service weapon of a policeman. It remains to be seen if the J&K Police will at least try to act or will yet again turn a blind eye towards Mir's unlawful behavior", NC Spokesman Junaid Azim Mattu said.

Hakim Yasin refutes his unconditional support to BJP 
RK News
Srinagar: While refuting news reports regarding his unconditional support to BJP, Peoples Democratic Front President Hakim Mohammad Yasin said he has been quoted out of context.
In a statement Hakim Yasin said that he has been misquoted in the report. “The bigger parties have a role to play and it is up to them to form the government. But the role of smaller parties is also important like 2002 and we will play our role.”
“I am ready to serve people of Kashmir and particularly people of Khansahib constituency in whatever capacity I am asked. I will support any party which is for the betterment and development of Kashmir.”
On the media reports about his offer of support to BJP, the MLA Khansahib said, “Deliberations and discussions over the issue are on and final call is yet to be taken. I’m ready to offer support to any government which is for the interests of Kashmiris. I won’t compromise on the interests of Kashmiris at any cost.”
However, he said, that it was in the best interests of Kashmiris that the elected government takes over without any delay. “People have high hopes with their representatives and it is high time that new government is formed which can alleviate the sufferings and miseries of people.”

Soz backs PDP
RK NEWS
Srinagar: State Congress Chief Prof Saif-ud-Din Soz Thursday has said PDP should be allowed to form government in state and said certain power hungry –political groups and individuals are trying to subvert the democratic Verdict of the people in the just concluded election.
Hinting at support to PDP, he said it is common knowledge and perception, a suave, experienced and forward -looking politician like Mufti Mohammad Sayeed should be allowed to lead a Coalition Government in the State with the support of other likeminded Parties/Groups. “That way alone the people’s verdict would truly be respected”.
He said RSS – BJP leadership would be well-advised to resist the temptation of cobbling a coalition that only deepens the polarization on religious and regional considerations, which is, to say the least, detrimental to the integrity of the State.
Soz said RSS-BJP leadership should also appreciate the sensitivity of this border State and not indulge in any kind of horse-trading, giving priority to the parochial interests. That kind of short-sighted political arrangement would certainly attract a Social Commotion and spoil the gains from a credible, free and fair Election concluded recently.”

status_message:
Arun Jaitley holds key meet amid political crisis in JK
RK News
Srinagar: The BJP's newly elected law-makers in Jammu and Kashmir are meeting now to decide on their presumptive Chief Minister. With 25 of the state's 87 assembly seats, must now decide whether to partner with a regional party and attempt to form the government, or serve as the Opposition.
Arun Jaitley and Ram Madhav have been deputed by the BJP from Delhi to supervise today's proceedings. Reports said that that the party is in touch with Omar Abdullah, with 15 seats for his National Conference, he is a viable option for an ally.
Abdullah has said so far that he is content to "wait and watch" the moves made by other parties; he has refused to reject the BJP as a political spouse, said that though "it is 99% no", he is "leaving a crack open". 
Amid talk of his meeting with BJP leaders, Abdullah tweeted today that he has not delayed his plans to travel to London.
The party that won the most seats is Mufti Mohammed Sayeed's Peoples Democratic Party (PDP), a group whose views on several key issues are the diametric opposite of the BJP's. A sustainable working relationship could be hard to engineer.

Three accused in acid attack arrested 
Sumaiya Yousuf
Srinagar: Police has finally achieved a major breakthrough in acid attack case that took place in Srinagar sometime ago by arresting all the three accused.

Police sources said that the trio was arrested from Bemina. The young girl was attacked in Soura area and she received major burn injuries and is being treated in Chennai.

Police is holding a news conference in the late afternoon to give details about the arrests.

status_message:
Trauma hospital in Kangan sans electricity 
Irfan Raina 
Kangan: Trauma Care Center Gund in Kangan area of Ganderbal district is without electricity for over two week causing its staff and patients huge inconvenience.
According to the reports, the Trauma Care hospital in Gund is reeling under darkness for over two week as the
transformer which is feeding it power supply got damaged.
Hospital officials said that though the transformer which was reinstalled two weeks before again developed snag.
They said that lack of electricity has made X-ray machines and other machines for conducting tests dysfunctional.
They said that repeated pleas to concerned JE and AEE have fallen to deaf ears.
Locals have demanded immediate installation of the transformer.

Rain, snowfall forecast in Kashmir
RK News
Srinagar: Rain and snowfall are expected in the Kashmir during next two days, the weather office said Sunday.
"We are expecting rain in the plains and snowfall in the higher reaches of Kashmir on Dec 22-23," a weather official said here.
"The night temperature has improved after more than a week though it continues to remain below the freezing point in the valley and Ladakh region," he said.
The minimum temperature rose to minus 1.8 in Srinagar Sunday against minus 4.4 Saturday.
The 40-day period of harsh winter known as 'Chilla Kalan' started here Sunday and will end on Jan 31. During the period, Kashmiris have to brave bitter cold. Even the maximum temperature hovers around zero degrees Celsius.

Tourist enjoy snow ride in Apharwat, Gulmarg on 21-12-2014. People in Kashmir are all set to witness the harshest winters referred to as Chilai Kalan that starts from today.Rising Kashmir/Tajamul Islam.

status_message:
Over 65 percent turnout in final phase of polling in JK 
RK News
Jammu: More than 65 per cent of the electorate exercised their franchise today in Jammu and Kashmir. At many places, voters lined up at polling stations.
Deputy Chief Minister Tara Chand and four of his cabinet colleagues were among 312 candidates whose fate was decided in the 20 seats spread across Jammu, Kathua and Rajouri districts.
After a record voter turnout in the previous four phases, particularly in the Kashmir, there were expectations of a high voter turnout in this phase. 
BJP has high stakes in this phase as of the 20 seats going to polls, it had got the most (10) seats in the 2008 Assembly elections followed by Congress (five seats), National Conference (2 seats), PDP one and Independents two.
The five-phase election began on November 25. The counting of votes will take place on December 23.
RSS chief Mohan Bhagwat says conversions will continue.
Estimated total turnout in Jammu & Kashmir 65 per cent, 4 per cent more than last assembly poll turnout: EC after final phase polling ends.

BJP candidate Nirmal Singh, Ravinder Raina attacked
‘Raina, his supporter injured in assault in Nowshera’
RK News
Jammu: Two Bharatiya Janta Party (BJP) candidates were today attacked in Nowshera and Billawar areas of Rajouri district allegedly by the political party goon leaving Nowshera candidate Ravinder Raina and his supporter wounded.
According to the sources, the cavalcade of BJP candidate Nowshera Ravinder Raina was allegedly targeted by the opposition political party (name withheld) when he was passing though Lambari area.
“The attackers damaged the vehicle carrying BJP candidate and wounded Rania and his supporter before leaving the area,” sources said, adding police on receiving information rushed there.
They evacuated the injured to the hospital for treatment and then, he was referred to GMC Hospital in Jammu for advanced treatment. Condition of Raina was stated to be stable and out of danger. Meanwhile, noisy protest demonstration started in Nowshera which was continue till the filling of this report.
Besides this, Dr Nirmal Singh, BJP candidate for Billawar assembly seat (Kathua) was attacked at Thara Kalwal allegedly by the seven to eight Congress miscreants, as per a press statement issued by the Nirmal Singh.
Police have started investigation in both the cases.
