status_message:
Pak GHQ attack mastermind Dr Usman executed
RK News
Islamabad: Aqeel alias Dr Usman and Arshad Mehmood have been executed in Faisalabad on Friday night, in the first capital punishment carried out in Pakistan since Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif lifted the moratorium on the death penalty.
Usman a former soldier of the army’s medical corps, was executed in relation to an attack on the headquarters of the Pakistan Army in 2009 in Rawalpindi. Arshad Mehmood, was executed for an assassination attempt on former military ruler, General (retd.) Pervez Musharraf.
The black warrant for Dr Usman was signed by Army Chief General Raheel Sharif late on Thursday night.
Dr Usman, who was caught injured during the Oct 10 raid on the army headquarters by militants, was sentenced to death in 2011 by a military court which had awarded prison terms to others in the GHQ attack case.
Apart from Dr Usman, who was caught during the attack, other serviceman and five civilians were found guilty of abetment.
Their trial by the military court, which was headed by a brigadier, had lasted over five months and had taken place at an undisclosed location.
Mehmood, who was a trooper, was among the five sentenced to be hanged for their role in an Al Qaeda-inspired assassination attempt on Musharraf’s life in late 2003.
Musharraf, who was in power at the time, narrowly escaped the bid when two suicide car bombers rammed his motorcade on Dec 25, 2003, in Rawalpindi. Fifteen people were killed in that attack.
Mehmood and civilians Zubair Ahmed, Rashid Bhatti, Rashid Qureshi, Ghulam Sarwar and Akhlaque Ahmed were convicted in the case.

RK News
Pulwama: Police Friday arrested a tipper driver and his two associates for allegedly murdering and raping a 21 year old girl in South Kashmir’s Pulwama district.
Divulging information about the brutal incident SSP Pulwama Tajindar Singh said that Muhammad Ramzan Bhat a resident of Wanpora, Newa Pulwama had lodged a missing report about her daughter on November 26 in police station Kakapora. He said that Bhat’s daughter was working in a Pencil Factory located at Okho Kakapora and had gone missing on Nov 26.
He added that police had zeroed in on all tipper drivers plying on Pulwama-Pampora route and during the course of interrogation, it came to fore that the victim had sought lift from one Zahoor Ahmed Bhat son of Muhammad Sultan resident of Kujru Budgam. The accused during interrogation reveled that he raped the girl and dumped her body with the help of his two associates later on.

Islamabad: Top Lashkar-e-Taiba commander Zaki-ur-Rehman Lakhvi, accused of plotting the 26/2011 terror attack on Mumbai in 2008, has been granted bail by an anti-terror court in Pakistan. 
The Islamabad court granted Lakhvi bail as it said the prosecution had been unable to provide evidence against him. Lakhvi was among seven people arrested in the Mumbai attacks trial in Pakistan in 2009 and was lodged at the Adiala jail in Rawalpindi. He had applied for bail yesterday.
The 54-year-old is accused of being one of the key plotters of the 26/2011 Mumbai attacks and also of training and handling the 10 Lashkar terrorists who sneaked into Mumbai and killed 166 people.

Pakistan lifts moratorium on death penalty 
RK News
Islamabad: Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharief lifted a moratorium on the death penalty on Wednesday, a day after Taliban gunmen attacked a school, killing 132 students and nine teachers, a government spokesman said. 

Mohiuddin Wani said Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif had approved the decision of a ministerial committee to life the moratorium. 

"It was decided that this moratorium should be lifted. The prime minister approved," he said. 

Addressing a press conference, Nawaz Sharif said that "nothing can be more tragic for Pakistan than the way terrorists riddled innocent children with bullets."

Obama phones Nawaz, regrets Peshawar incident

RK News
Washington: US President Barack Obama telephoned Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif on Wednesday and expressed his condolences over the death of 141 people including 132 children killed in the attack on Peshawar's Army Public School.

Obama called Sharif and conveyed his deepest condolences and sympathies from the people of United States on the brutal massacre.

Indian schools observe silence over Peshawar massacre
RK News
New Delhi: Indian lawmakers and schools observed a two-minute silence over the massacre in Peshawar that claimed 141 lives on Tuesday. 
Apart from the two-minute silence, the schools also held special prayers to commemorate the victims of the attack.
The show of solidarity comes as Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi reached out to Pakistan in a telephone conversation last night with Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif.

Pakistan plunges into mourning
RK News
Islamabad: Tuesday’s militants attack in Peshawar has plunged Pakistan into deep mourning. Never has the country seen the kind of callous orchestration of an attack as witnessed yesterday on defenceless school children.

The government has announced a three-day mourning. Schools are closed in parts of the country, a number of educational institutions will remain open and also offer prayers for the victims of the massacre. 

Several parts of Pakistan also saw people gathering for condemnation, mourning and candlelight vigils Tuesday night to show solidarity with the children. 
Meanwhile, most of those killed will likely be laid to rest today.

status_message:
Historic voter turnout in Srinagar 
RK News
Srinagar: Srinagar, the capital city Kashmir region, Sunday with a record voter turnout in the fourth phase of assembly elections in the state.
A total of 24.41 percent votes were polled till 3 pm in the eight constituencies of Srinagar which is the highest since the region erupted in violence in early nineties which was centered in the city. The final figures are expected to touch 30 percent mark.
In 2008 elections, Srinagar recorded 21.09 percent voter turnout while the figure for 2002 and 1996 assembly elections were 5.13 percent and 19.20 percent respectively.
The Sonawar constituency led the polling race in Srinagar with a record 40.65 percent votes polled till 3 pm. The constituency saw 36.66 percent turnout in 2008, 9.96 percent in 2002 and 34.71 percent in 1996 assembly elections.
Chief minister Omar Abdullah is contesting from here and he said Sunday that he was not concerned about the anti-incumbency against his party in the region.
Political analysts see the surge in voter turnout as a careful calibration of the regional parties to keep the Hindu right-wing Bhartiya Janta Party at bay in the Muslim majority state.

status_message:
Kashmir set for IV Phase elections 
Daanish Bin Nabi
Srinagar: Amid heavy deployment of paramilitary forces and Police Jammu and Kashmir is all for set for the 4th Phase election in which 14.7 lakh electorate will seal fate of 182 candidates including Chief Minister Omar Abdullah and three NC and Congress ministers today.
18 assembly constituencies will go to polls on Sunday. The electorates will seal the fate of Omar in Sonawar constituency. The fate of three sitting ministers—Rural Development Minister, Ali Mohammad Sagar (Khanyar seat), Haj and Auqaf Minister Peerzada Sayeed (Kokernag), Tourism Minister G A Mir (Dooru) and Speaker Mubarak Gul (Iddgah) will also be sealed in the Electronic Voting Machines (EVMs).
Hazratbal assembly seat, Zadibal, Habbakadal, Amirakadal, Sonawar, Batamaloo, Anantnag, Shangus, Bijbehara, Pahalgam, Wachi and Shopian in Kashmir and Samba and Vijapypur in Jammu will also be going to polls in the 4th phase of elections.
A total of 14.7 lakh people are eligible to cast vote at 1890 polling stations in the assembly constituencies.
The highest number of 1.2 lakh electorate is in Batamaloo constituency while lowest number of 51010 voters is in Khanyar segment.
The 5th and final phase of elections will be held on December 20 and results will be declared on December 23.

LFB condoles demise of AG Hafiz, expresses solidarity with RK family 
RK News
Srinagar: Literary Forum Bandipora (LFB) has condoled the sad demise of noted Trade Union leader and journalist Abdul Gani Hafiz.
In a statement issued today, LFB President Mubashir Saleem Nazki expressed condolence with Managing Editor Rising Kashmir Ayaz Hafiz who is son of the leader and also expressed condolence to Editor-in-chief Rising Kashmir Shujaat Bukhari who is son-in-law of late Hafiz.
A delegation of LFB lead by Secretary Tariq Rasool and spokesperson Sheikh Saleem visited the bereaved family and expressed solidarity with them. LFB expressed condolences with whole Rising Kashmir Family. 
LFB also held a condolence meeting in Bandipora in which LFB members prayed for the departed soul. The condolence meeting was also attended by Vice Presidents Gul Tanveer and Showkat Sufi, General Secretary Mansoor Muntazir, Mir Dachigami, GN Zahid and Peer Mubashir.

status_message:
Mufti visits residence of Abdul Gani Hafiz
RK News
Srinagar: Democratic Party (PDP) patron, Mufti Mohammad Sayeed Saturday visited the residence of veteran trade union leader and journalist, Abdul Gani Hafiz, who passed away on Thursday, 11 Dec, to offer his condolences with the bereaved family.
The deceased was the father-in-law of the eminent journalist and Editor of the daily Rising Kashmir, Shuj’aat Bukhari.
Speaking on the occasion, Mufti termed the late Hafiz Sahib a multifaceted personality who courageously fought for the rights of government employees and downtrodden sections of the society all through his life. 
The PDP patron said late Hafiz Sahib was not only a social worker of great repute but a prolific writer whose writings would continue to inspire the generations to come in.
Expressing solidarity with the bereaved family, Mufti prayed for the everlasting peace of the deceased soul.

Militants frustrated after the ongoing successful assembly elections: Shafiq Mir  
RK News
Jammu: While condemning the killing of a Sarpanch in Sopore area of Baramulla, All Jammu and Kashmir Panchayat Conference Chairman, Shafiq Mir has said that militants and other antidemocratic forces must read the writings on wall and shun the path of violence against the people of the state having opposite ideology. 
In his reaction, Shafiq Mir who heads the Panchayat Members Body in the state of Jammu and Kashmir said that the militants got frustrated after the ongoing successful assembly elections in the state and they have started targeting the basic pillars of democracy in the state. 
It is pertinent to mention here that two Saarpanches have been killed in the state during the ongoing assembly elections. Earlier, a week ago, a Sarpanch namely Mohammad Sultan was killed in Shopian area South Kashmir and in latest incident one more Sarpanch namely Ghulam Mohammad Mir (62) has been killed allegedly by the militants during the ensuing night of Friday and Saturday. Before killing him, he was kidnapped from his house.

Earlier High Court had asked state to inform the court about the expenditure of funds provided by center post floods.

Modi pays tributes to soldiers killed in 2001 Parliament attack
RK News
New Delhi: On the anniversary of the 2001 attack on Parliament, Prime Minister Narendra Modi, Lok Sabha Speaker Sumitra Mahajan and other parliamentarians paid tribute to the soldiers who lost their lives during the attack.
Home Minister Rajnath Singh, Foreign Minister Sushma Swaraj, former prime minister Manmohan Singh, BJP leader LK Advani and Congress President Sonia Gandhi were among others who paid tribute.
Mohammad Afzal Guru a Kashmiri was convicted and given death sentence for his role in the December 2001 attack on the Indian Parliament.

Modi in Kathua, lashes out at Cong, NC, PDP
Syed Amjad
Jammu: Prime Minister Narendra Modi who arrived in Kathua today to address an election rally which was attending by enthusiastic people in large numbers 
Lashing out Congress, Modi in his speech said, “Congress in JK is an 'intruder' who entered in every government through back door and then back stab those with whom they remain in coalition.” 
Further lambasting regional parties National Conference and People Democratic Party he said, “Realise that your daughters and sons are not less than others. This is democracy of BJP where we don’t favour dynasty politics. We want to give power in the hands of people and farmers of Jammu and Kashmir.”
Lamenting on recent ceasefire violations Modi said people of Kathua fight with the country even they are not in uniform. They face Pak firing with dare and courage but recruitment in army for this place was stopped for such a patriot and courageous people.

status_message:
Acid attack culprits give slip to Police at airport
RK News
Srinagar: The two culprits involved in the acid attack on a college girl in Srinagar have given a slip to police at SheikH Ul Alam International Airport, a top police official said.
According to the police official, who wished not to be identified, said the two culprits were last seen at Sheikh Ul Alam International Airport, Srinagar today and were trying to leave the region.
"The two culprits were seen getting down from a white Maruti car 800 with 'MANSA' written on it at the airport," the official said.
The duo tried to book tickets for Delhi from a ticketing counter at the airport.
The official said they couldn't get tickets for the flight and left in hurry from the spot before police could nab them.
Police has requested airport authorities to handover the CCTV footage to identify the attackers.
The incident happened on Thursday morning in Soura locality when two men threw acid on a college girl. The girl was shifted to the hospital for the treatment. The victim has received serious burns injuries on her face and eye.
The police have launched a manhunt to nab the attackers and requested people to help them in hunting down the culprits.
Police said the two men were driving a car with "MANSA" sticker pasted on its shield.
The incident was widely condemned by people across the region. Hundreds of students today also hit streets to protest against the crime.

Grenade attack in Anantnag 
Shah Suhail 
Anantnag: Three police men were hurt after the Sherbagh police post of this
South Kashmir town, was attacked with a hand grenade by unidentified
militants. 
According to reports suspected militants hurled a hand grenade at the
police post at about 8:50 PM Thursday evening.

The grenade, a senior police official said, exploded in the lawns of
the police post injuring three on duty constables.

"The constables have been rushed to the district hospital here," the
official said.

He identified the injured constables as Zahoor Ahmad, Ashiq Hussain
and Farooq Ahmad.

"The doctors at the hospital say that all of the injured are out of
danger and stable," the official said.

Mehbooba condemns acid attack on girl

Dr Sameer Kaul extends free medical assistance
RK News
Srinagar: Strongly condemning the incident of acid attack on a girl Law student in Nowshera Srinagar, the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) President, Ms Mehbooba Mufti has said the incident is horrific, inhuman and against the basic human values.

 In a statement, she said that society need to stands up against these heinous acts and needs to introspect and restore the value system that used to hold women in high esteem.

 While conveying her feelings of solidarity to the victim and her family in this hour of pain, she hoped that the perpetrators of this dastardly crime are expeditiously brought to justice for appropriate punishment.

Meanwhile, the reputed surgeon and National Spokesperson of the Peoples Democratic Party (PDP), Dr Sameer Kaul has extended complete free medical assistance to the victim.

Landmine planted in Shopian

Shopian: A Land mine was detected beneath a bridge near Harmain Shopian, just three kilometers from Chief Minister Omar Abdullah rally venue in Vehil area today. However, Police and bomb disposal squad have reached on spot.

Acid attack update: Victim is stable, under observation 
Manzoor ul Hassan
Srinagar: The girl who was attacked with acid by some unidentified persons this morning has suffered serious burn injuries on her right eye, right side of face and a portion of forehead, doctors said.
According to doctors at SKIMS Soura it is difficult to tell the exact severity of burns by the acid as the victim is still under observation.
"She is stable as there is no threat to her life from the burns. We have still put her under close observation in the department of plastic surgery for 24-48 hours. She has also undergone checkup at SKIMS Hospital Bemina for the injured right eye. Specialists will review her injuries again tomorrow to tell the exact situation and start the further treatment," HoD Plastic Surgery Dr Inam Zaroo told Rising Kashmir.

Acid attack update: Police launches manhunt
RK News
Srinagar: A young woman suffered dreadful injuries after having corrosive liquid thrown in her face outside her college in Srinagar. She was outside her college in Soura when unknown persons sprinkled acid on her face. 
Reports said the girl was nearing her college in Tawheedabad when some unknown persons on a car halted in front of her and suddenly squirted the acid from a bottle.
She was shifted to SK Institute of Medical Sciences in Soura. Doctors at the hospital said they shifted her to JVC Medical College and Hospital as she had injuries in eyes. 
Meanwhile, Police said a manhunt has been started to nab the culprits. Police in a statement said that, "The attackers fled in a white Maruti car having a sticker “MANSA” pasted on its rear glass. Anybody having any information regarding the white car having a “MANSA” sticker pasted on it may please intimate police on 9596770587, 9596770867 or police control room on 100," he said.

Veteran trade union leader A G Hafiz passes away

His Nimaz e Jinaza will be offered in Natipora after Zuhur prayers.
Hafiz was father of RK Managing Editor Hafiz Ayaz Gani and father-in-law of noted journalist and Rising Kashmir Editor Shujaat Bukhari

status_message:
J&K take historic win over Mumbai
RK News
Srinagar: Jammu & Kashmir shocked domestic heavyweights Mumbai with a historic four-wicket win by chasing down 237 on the last day at the Wankhede Stadium. The effort was led by opener Shubham Khajuria's 78 and the win was sealed by an unbeaten 41 from Hardeep Singh after captain Parvez Rasool scored 32.
J&K resumed on 58 for 1 and Mumbai dismissed Bandeep Singh in the fourth over of the day before the visitors replied with a fifty partnership, and Rasool and Hardeep ensured they did not stutter much despite losing four more wickets, two of those taken by Vishal Dabholkar.
Khahuria was named Man of the Match for his fifty in second innings and 107 in the first.

status_message:
Ready to assist in resolving Kashmir dispute if requested: Ban
PTI
New Delhi: UN chief Ban Ki Moon has expressed readiness to engage with India and Pakistan in resolving the Kashmir issue if requested by both and asked them to resume talks to reach an agreement that would serve their security interests as well as that of the region.
 “As I have stated in the past, if both countries request it, I am ready to engage further to assist in resolving this issue,” the Secretary General said.
Reiterating that peace in Jammu and Kashmir can be achieved only through dialogue, Ban called on the two countries to resume discussions and said that an agreement on Kashmir would serve the security interests of both countries as well as that of the region.

status_message:
My duty to deliver promises Vajpayee made to you, says Modi 
RK News
Srinagar: Prime Minister Narendra Modi in his address in Sringar said, “First time since 1983 that anyone has dared to hold a rally at this stadium. I will return the love you have given to me with interest. I will return it with development. There has not been a single month that I haven't come to J&K since I became PM.” 
He further said that, “I have come here to share your sorrows, not to take anything from you. You have given me a lot of love, what can be greater than that. I have to fulfill Atalji's dream of insaniyat, kashmiriyat and Jamhooriyat.
Laying stress on development he said, “Tourism is a sector which offers employment and a daily wage to every sector of the society. Pahad ka paani aur paha ki jawani, dono pahad ke kaam nahi aati - I want to change this idiom. There should be no discrimination. My mantra is sabka saath, sabka vikaas. There should be no area, section of society, family - there should be no discrimination between them. 
Lashing out at NC led government he said, “I'm sorry to use harsh words, but when the floods struck the government here was sleeping. I will deploy the whole government at your service. Corruption has finished this state. People here wanted the relief money to be transferred to their accounts directly and not to the state government. They did not have faith in the government here but they trusted Modi.
About corruption he said, “Corruption is our biggest challenge till that goes, the common man in Kashmir will not be benefitted PM Modi targeted Omar Abdullah, says when floods struck, state government was sleeping. The people in Kutch told me leaders keep talking about border issues with Pakistan, not of development. I shifted the focus in Kutch to development. Today, it is the fastest growing district in India. If Kutch can develop, so can Kashmir. 
About the recent militants related deaths in Kashmir he said, “Since independence 33,000 policemen (not armed forces) have died in protecting civilians in this state. But for the first time in 30 years, the Army admitted its mistake. This was under BJP rule. There was an inquiry and cases filed against those guilty of shooting at the 2 youth.

People from Jammu being brought for PM's Srinagar rally: Omar

RK News
Srinagar: Taking a dig at the Prime Minister Narendra Modi, Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister and Working President of National Conference Omar Abdullah Monday alleged that people were brought from Jammu for the former’s election rally in Srinagar.
Taking to micro-blogging website Twitter, Omar said: “2 trainloads of supporters are being brought in from Banihal in Jammu. Why not just have the rally there?”
Hitting at Sajad Lone who had earlier called Modi as his “elder brother”, Omar claimed that people from Kupwara, the former’s bastion, are being sent to attend the rally at Sher-i-Kashmir stadium.
“So @sajadlone is sending about 80 vehicles of supporters from Kupwara to help his "big brother" make up the numbers,” Omar tweeted.
He also expressed surprise over what he said Congress’ support for the rally.
“Amazingly even Cong supported "leaders" have been asked to contribute people to the BJP rally. Politics makes for strange bedfellows ,” wrote Omar.

status_message:
Complete shutdown in Kashmir on Modi’s visit
Daanish Bin Nabi
Srinagar: Strict curfew has been imposed in old city of Srinagar, while a complete shutdown is being observed elsewhere in Kashmir in response to the strike call given by Separatists groups against the visit of Prime Minister Narendra Modi to Kashmir.
Reports said all shops, offices, commercial establishments and educational institutions in valley are closed while public traffic is completely off the roads. 
Meanwhile, CRPF troopers and policemen are deployed in Maharaj Gunj, Khanyar, Rainawari, Nowhatta, Safa Kadal Jehangir Chowk, Iqbal Park, Hyderpora, Batmaloo, where curfews-like restrictions were imposed since Sunday night to foil protests against Modi’s visit.
No traffic moment is allowed beyond Jehangir Chowk towards Lal Chowk, areas beyond Dalgate upto Pantha Chowk are also kept under tight vigil and no one is allowed to move in these areas. 
Donning riot gear and carrying automatic rifles, forces maintained tight vigil on the movement of the civilians. Besides blocking lanes, by lanes and streets of the downtown with barricades and spools of razor wire, the forces had also placed armoured vehicles at important crossings.
The police have also placed Hurriyat Conference (G) chairman, Syed Ali Geelani and several other leaders of the conglomerate under house arrest.

Haryana Police clarifies
It was senior-Junior class not any regional bias

Sheikh saleem

Srinagar: The superintendent of Police of District Yamuna (Haryana) Ved Prakash while talking to Rising Kashmir rebutted the allegations that the attack was on basis of regionalism. He said the fight started between two senior and junior students- both of J&K state. “Both called their local friends the next day and fought each other,” he said.
He said as the news reached to him about the incident, he immediately send DySP to the spot and got the injured admitted in hospital. He also denied any involvement of local person in the incident. He said both the groups were students of the college and among them some were the local students who reside in the vicinity. None other than the college was involved in the attack. 
He assured full security to the Kashmiri students and appealed parents not to worry about their wards. “We asked some parents to visit the college so that they are satisfied regarding the security of their wards,” he added.

Srinagar: General Officer Commanding (GOC) Srinagar-based 15 Corps Lt Gen Subroto Saha Sunday said 100 militants have been killed this year compared to 62 killed last year during the same period.
He said there were 51 counterinsurgency operation conducted this year by the Army.

Kashmiri students beaten in Haryana

Some students hurt in the incident are said to be critical

Srinagar: Kashmiri students studying at Global Research Institute for Management and Technology in Yamna Nagar Haryana have reportedly been hospitalised after being attacked by local goons. 
Some of the students hurt in the attack are said to be critical.
The report said the incident happened Saturday afternoon when some local goons manhandled Kashmiri students for being asked to be in queue during lunch time in the college canteen.
The students were beaten up by rods and sticks and chased away for miles with the assistance of a local village head. The frightened students have taken shelter in a local police station.
Even after five hours of the incident, college authorities have failed to secure the students or take any action against the attackers.
Local police, according to reports, is still trying to collect information on what led to the incident. No arrests have been made so far.

status_message:
Kashmir set for second phase of elections 
Daanish Bin Nabi
Srinagar: Kashmir is set for second phase of assembly elections which will seal the fate of 175 candidates. As many as 18 Assembly segments, spread over five districts two in the Valley and three in Jammu region-will go to polls on Tuesday to decide the fate of 175 candidates which includes the lone woman minister in the National Conference-Congress coalition government Sakina Ittoo.
Of the 18 constituencies, Handwara in north Kashmir Kupwara district will be the focus of attention as separatist-turned-mainstream politician Sajjad Gani Lone is making debut in Assembly elections.
Deputy Speaker of the present Assembly and PDP leader Sartaj Madni will be seeking a third consecutive term from Devsar Assembly segment.
Ittoo, is among the four ministers in the fray for Noorabad Assembly segment going to polls on Tuesday. Other ministers from her party include Law Minister Saifullah Mir (Kupwara) and Chaudhary Mohammad Ramzan (Handwara) while Ajaz Ahmad Khan (Gool Arnas) is from Congress.
Kulgam constituency in south Kashmir will also be in focus as the CPI (M) face in Jammu and Kashmir, Mohammad Yousuf Tarigami, is seeking fourth consecutive term.
A total of over 12 lakh voters will exercise their franchise at 1,900 polling stations established in the constituencies going to polls in second phase.

Arun Jaitely to visit Srinagar on 3 Dec
Sumaiya Yusuf
Srinagar: While releasing its ‘Vision Document’ here in Srinagar Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) Monday said that Minister for Finance Arun Jaitley is slated to visit Srinagar on December 3rd.

BJP leaders said that, “Arun Jaitely will visit Srinagar on December 3rd. On his visit to Kashmir, he will talk with the people here about BJP policies on Kashmir, they said. 

BJP is aiming to win 44+ seats in the ongoing assembly elections in Jammu and Kashmir.

28 school drop-outs, 55 crorepatis contesting in 2nd phase
PTI
Srinagar: Out of the 175 candidates in fray in 18 constituencies of Jammu and Kashmir which are going to polls in the second phase on Tuesday, 97 or more than 50 % are not graduates and nine have criminal cases against them. 

The affidavits submitted by the candidates along with their nomination papers suggest that nine of them are illiterate while 28 are school drop-outs, according to Association of Democratic Reforms (ADR). 

A total of 55 candidates or 31% are crorepatis and have declared their properties to be worth over Rs one crore. There are only eight women candidates in the fray. 

Kuldeep Raj Dubey, BJP candidate from Gool Arnas has declared highest assets worth Rs 14.10 crores, while five other candidates, including separatist-turned-mainstream Sajad Gani Lone, have declared more than Rs 10 crores worth of assets in their affidavits. 

Lone, who is contesting on Handwara seat, has assets worth Rs 13.98 crores including moveable assets to the tune of Rs 38.45 lakh. 

Interestingly, a total of 11 candidates have declared zero assets in their affidavits, while five candidates have declared liabilities of Rs one crore and above. 

"Nine candidates are illiterate, two are class five pass, while 26 are class eight pass and 30 have listed their educational qualification as class 10," ADR said. 

While 30 candidates have passed class 12, 18 are simple graduates and 26 professional graduates. 

"There are 25 post-graduate candidates, two have a doctorate degree and five have not listed their qualifications," the analysis by the ADR said. 

Nine, a total of five per cent, candidates have declared criminal cases against them, while six of them have serious criminal cases, including kidnapping, rioting and forgery registered against them. 

Balwant Singh Mankotia of National Panthers Party from Udhampur constituency, in Jammu regions, has declared a case related to kidnapping (IPC Section 363) against him in his poll affidavit. 

Mankotia is also facing the charges of rioting, along with his colleague from Reasi constituency, Balwan Singh, BJP's Mendhar assembly segment candidate Zulfqar Hussain Khan and an independent candidate on Handwara seat Ajaz Ahmad Sofi. 

Cheating and dishonestly, criminal intimidation, forgery for purpose of cheating, voluntarily causing hurt by dangerous weapons or means and charges related to Act of endangering life or personal safety of others are the other cases the contesting candidates are facing. 

109 candidates or 62% have not declared their income tax details. 

Though some candidates may be exempted from filing income tax returns under rules, there are 20 candidates with assets worth more than Rs 1 crore, who have not declared such details. 

Party-wise the National Conference (NC) has the lowest number of such candidates who have not filed their IT details – five, while Bahujan Samajwadi Party (BSP) and National Panthers Party (NPP) have the highest of 12 and 11 respectively. 

Nine candidates of Congress, nine of BJP, eight of Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) and four out of five Peoples Conference (PC) – headed by separatist-turned-mainstream Sajad Gani Lone – have not filed their I-T returns. 

There are 74 candidates who have not submitted their PAN details. 

Party-wise, Peoples Democratic Party (PDP) has the highest number of crorepatis – nine out of 16 (56%), while Congress too has nine but out of 18. National Conference (NC) has eight crorepati candidates, BJP has seven and 12 out of 52 Independent candidates have declared assets worth more than Rs 1 crore. 

The average value of assets per candidate contesting in the second phase of the polls is Rs 1.41 crore. 

Among major parties, the average assets per PDP candidates is Rs 2.01 crore, for Congress candidates it is Rs 1.78 crore, while for NC Rs 1.74 crore and for BJP it is Rs 1.54 crore. 

There are five candidates who have liabilities of over Rs one crore. Meenakshi Sharma, an independent candidate from Reasi. has the highest liabilities of Rs 4.79 crore. 

103 candidates are in the age group of 25 to 50 years, while 68 are in the age group of 51 to 80. 

Nine assembly segments each are going to polls in the second phase in both Jammu and Kashmir regions of the state. 

They are spread over five districts of Kupwara, Kulgam, Reasi, Udhampur and Poonch. 

The electorate in the constituencies of Gulabgarh, Reasi, Gool Arnas, Udhampur, Chenani, Ramnagar, Surankote, Mendhar and Poonch Haveli in Jammu region and Karnah, Kupwara, Lolab, Handwara, Langate, Noorabad, Kulgam, Home-Shalibugh and Devsar in Kashmir Valley will vote on December 2.

Udhampur: Prime Minister Narendra Modi Friday alleged Congress, National Conference and PDP of “looting” money meant for the development for Jammu and Kashmir.

Earlier, a special plane carrying Modi landed at the technical area of Jammu airport around noon.
 “I visited J&K in the months of August, September, October and November,” Modi said adding “I will be visiting in December as well.”

“Every month I come here, there has been no PM who has visited J&K so often. Lakhs of families suffered during floods, I did not delay my visit even for a moment, after reviewing situation sent assistance for your service,” Modi said.

“I have come here with the aim of development and I have also come here to wipe your tears. We have decided to give proper assistance to J&K but we will make sure where this money is going,” PM Modi said.

status_message:
10 dead in Arina  
RK News
Jammu: A group of four or five militants were holed up for several hours in an abandoned army bunker near the border with Pakistan. 10 people, four militants, three civilians, and three army soldiers were killed in the encounter which began at 8 am.
Eight militants reportedly crossed from Pakistan this morning into India near Arnia in the Jammu region. 
It's not clear if they shot at an army column on patrol before taking refuge in the bunker. Senior army sources said that ceasefire violations by Pakistan at the border this morning may have served as cover for the militants to cross over. However, the Border Security Force denied this.
Prime Minister Narendra Modi is scheduled to visit Udhampur which is near Arnia tomorrow to address rallies for the state election. Voting is being held over five days; the first phase on Tuesday saw a record voter turnout of nearly 72 per cent.

Finally handshake for Modi and Nawaz 
RK News
New Delhi: The summit of South Asian leaders in Nepal was salvaged at the last minute with all eight countries clinching a last-minute deal to create a regional electricity grid. 
That agreement was reached at a day-long mountain retreat near the Nepali capital of Kathmandu, where Prime Minister Narendra Modi and his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif were present.  
The Pakistani and Indian leaders shook hands at the retreat, said Nepal's Foreign Minister Mahendra Bahadur Pandey, but gave no details. Then came a public handshake at the end of the summit—at a photo op, Modi and Nawaz were seen smiling and talking. Until the thaw at the retreat, Modi and Sharif had cold-shouldered each other. They barely exchanged pleasantries at a dinner last night; earlier yesterday, as Sharif got up to address the summit, Modi was seen pointedly reading a pamphlet.

Army officer, 3 civilians killed in Arina 
RK News
Arina: A Junior Commissioned Officer or JCO of the Indian Army was killed when four militants entered a reportedly abandoned Army bunker near the Pindi post, barely three kilometres from the International Border in Jammu and Kashmir's Arnia sector. 
The militants, who are believed to have entered the bunker on Wednesday night, were challenged by Army personnel. The JCO sustained fatal bullet injuries in the ensuing exchange of fire. 
Three civilians were also killed in the encounter; which is still reportedly going on. The Army has cordoned off the area.
Three militants have also been killed in the encounter, said Army sources.
The initial alarm about the militants was raised by villagers this morning, after which the Army rushed in its Quick Reaction Team. 
Ceasefire violations have also been reported at the border outposts at Pindi and Nairianpur.
Jammu and Kashmir Chief Minister Omar Abdullah said it "cannot be a coincidence" that the Arnia militant attack came as Prime Minister Narendra Modi and his Pakistani counterpart Nawaz Sharif attended the SAARC summit in Nepal.
"The timing of the attack in Arnia can't be a coincidence. My condolences to the family of the army officer killed in Arnia," Abdullah wrote on micro-blogging site Twitter.

Reports said PM Modi and Nawaz Sharif exchanged hellos but had no separate conversation during the retreat at Dhulikhel, which is famous for its view of the Himalayas.
PM Modi and Mr Sharif have shared frosty vibes since the two-day summit began on Wednesday and did not even look at each other when they shared a dais in the opening session.
On Wednesday, PM Modi had two-way talks with most leaders except Nawaz Sharif. Chances of a meeting between the two to restart India-Pakistan talks faded after Mr Sharif told reporters that "the ball is in India's court." India says Pakistan needs to commit to "meaningful dialogue" before they can meet at the summit.
Pakistan has blocked key proposals to integrate energy grids and free up road and rail movement.

status_message:
70 percent voter turnout in JK: Election Commission
RK News
Srinagar: With long queues and brisk polling through the day, JK Tuesday saw a voter turnout of 70 per cent in the first phase of assembly elections, the Election Commission has said.
The 70% voter turnout in this phase is a big increase over the 64.97% in the last assembly elections in these areas, the commission said, also noting that voting was peaceful.
It credited the higher voting percentage to "good security, confidence building and the zeal of voters"
Voting was held in 15 of Jammu and Kashmir's 87 constituencies - six seats in the Jammu division, five segments in the Kashmir valley and four in Ladakh.
No militancy-related incident was reported in Jammu and Kashmir today. Polling was briefly disrupted at Barsoo in Ganderbal district after clashes broke out between two groups, but resumed soon.
For the first time there is a four-way battle between the Congress, Chief Minister Omar Abdullah's National Conference, the Jammu and Kashmir People's Democratic Party (PDP) and the BJP, which has set itself the target of winning 50 plus seats in the 87-member assembly, with an eye on forming government.

First phase of JK polls ends peacefully
RK News
Srinagar: First phase of polling ended peacefully Tuesday in 15 assembly constituencies in Jammu and Kashmir as no major incident of violence has been reported from anywhere.
A total of 12 sitting MLAs, including seven ministers, were among 123 candidates whose fate was sealed in the Electronic Voting Machines (EVM’s).
The Assembly segments which went to polls in the first phase include Gurez, Bandipora, Sonawari, Kangan and Ganderbal (in Kashmir), Bhaderwah, Ramban and Banihal (in Jammu division); and Nobra, Leh, Kargil and Zanskar (in Ladakh).

Nawaz asks Obama to raise Kashmir Issue during India visit
PTI
Islamabad:  Pakistan Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif has asked US President Barack Obama to take up the Kashmir issue with the Narendra Modi government when he travels to India in January next year.
Sharif made the request when President Obama telephoned him on Friday, informing him about his forthcoming India visit to attend the Republic Day celebrations as the Chief Guest.
"The Prime Minister also urged President Obama to take up the cause of Kashmir with the Indian leadership, as its early resolution would bring enduring peace, stability and economic cooperation to Asia," said a statement from the Pakistan Prime Minister's Office on the discussions between the two leaders.
During the telephonic conversation, Sharif recalled an invitation he extended to President Obama last year in Washington and conveyed the expectation of the people of Pakistan to welcome the US President to the country sometime in the future.
Sharif also alleged that New Delhi subsequently took "unfortunate steps, including cancellation of Foreign Secretary-level talks" and "firing across the LoC resulting in civilian casualties" which showed that "India was averse to normalisation of relations with Pakistan."
The Pakistani PM said his country "remains open to the resumption of bilateral dialogue, the onus is on India to create a conducive environment in this regard."
"President Obama expressed his understanding for our position," the statement added.
The two leaders also discussed the regional situation with Sharif referring to the improvement of Pakistan's relations with Afghanistan as manifest in President Ashraf Ghani's recent visit to Islamabad.
President Obama appreciated Prime Minister Sharif's efforts in this regard and called it pivotal for the peace and stability in the region, the statement said.
Later, the White House also confirmed that President Obama had called Sharif on Friday. "I can confirm that the President did speak with PM (Prime Minister) Sharif," Mark Stroh, spokesman of the National Security Council, said.

status_message:
Shahi Imam has no right to anoint son: Delhi HC
RK News
New Delhi: The Delhi High Court on Friday declared that the dastarbandi ceremony anointing Jama Masjid Shahi Imam Ahmed Bukhari’s son Shaban as the Naib Imam “shall not vest or create any right” in his favor.
Taking note of submissions made by the Central government and the Waqf board on Thursday, the court of Chief Justice G Rohini and justice RS Endlaw held that it is “of the opinion” that in the face of the contentions of the petitioners, supported by the Waqf board, the Dastarbandi ceremony scheduled on November 22 even if not stayed will not amount to anointment/appointment of the said son of Bukhari as the Naib Imam of Jama Masjid.”
The court also noted that since the Masjid was the residence of the Bukhari family, it “did not feel any need” to restrain the Imam from holding the ceremony in Jama Masjid. The court has also clarified that the anointment of Shaban Bukhari “or any other person as Naib Imam of the Jama Masjid shall be subject to further orders in this petition”.

status_message:
Awami Mutahida Mahaz releases manifesto 
RK News
Srinagar: Awami Mutahida Mahaz touted as Third Front Friday released its election manifesto in Srinagar the manifesto titled: “Towards a democratic alternative platform”- asserts that the people of Jammu and Kashmir are facing various stressful problems which have their roots in the political uncertainty and the presence of harsh anti-people laws and acts. 
The manifesto makes it clear that there is no military solution to the Kashmir issue and urges both India and Pakistan to show mature statesmanship and resolve the issue by sincere, sustained and meaningful dialogue.
The manifesto also promises full support for the complete rehabilitation of all those people who were forced to migrate from Pakistan administered Kashmir in 1947. 
Among other things the manifesto lays stress on resolving the various problems faced by youth of the state. It demands framing of a comprehensive employment policy, expansion of industrial sector and speedy filling up of vacant positions, besides regularization of all the casual and contractual workers for addressing the problem of acute unemployment.  
All the prisoners especially the youth, who are not involved in serious crimes, should be released and utmost care should be taken while dealing with the law and order situation. Public Safety Act, AFSPA and other such acts should be scraped at the earliest while the Chattergam like incidents should not be allowed to occur in future and the responsible security officials should be given exemplary punishment in order to restore the confidence of the people, enumerates the manifesto.
The manifesto concludes by expressing a strong hope that the people of the state, who are looking for an alternative and change, will vote in favour of the Mahaz candidates who can launch a struggle for the creation of an alternative socio-political and economic system in the state.

status_message:
BJP confident of winning over 44 seats in JK polls: Nadda
PTI  
Jammu: Expressing confidence over BJP accomplishing its ambitious 'Mission 44+' in the Jammu and Kashmir Assembly polls, Union Minister JP Nadda Wedneday said people were increasingly reposing faith in the party which has strengthened their resolve to form government in the state.
"BJP is fighting the Assembly elections in Jammu and Kashmir with a special strategy to come to power in the state.
BJP is confident of accomplishing its Mission 44+," Nadda told reporters in Jammu while campaigning for the party in the state where it aims to win at least 44 of a total 87 seats.
"We are watching enthusiasm and love of the people for BJP during our campaigning for some time now. People have created a wave-like effect for BJP in Jammu and Kashmir," the Union Health Minister added.
Nadda said whether it was Jammu, Leh in Ladakh or Srinagar in Kashmir valley, people were "reposing faith in the lotus and moving towards the party".
"The faith of people in BJP, have strengthened our endeavor and resolve to meet the target and form the government in the state. ...The party needs to consolidate its gains that have been speedily achieved during campaigning," the minister said.

No Ebola threat in India: Health Minister
RK News
New Delhi: Union Health Minister J.P. Nadda Wednesday assuaged fears of an Ebola outbreak in the country. He said despite the presence of an Indian national who has tested positive for the virus, there is no fear of contamination.
The 26 ­year old male who is currently in an isolation facility in the Delhi airport, is cured of Ebola, but will remain in isolation for the 21­day quarantine period, Nadda said. He said authorities at all ports of entry to the country have been asked to reinforce screening of arrivals to ensure there are no lapses.
“This individual too is cured of Ebola, but we decided to test him for the virus and found it in his semen. Since he can pass it through sexual contact, we have decided to quarantine him. He will be released only when his tests comes back negative. All precautions are being taken and there is no reason for panic,” an official of the Health Ministry said here on Wednesday.
The detection of the virus in the 26 ­year ­old man, who reached here on November 10, was a result of “extra caution” shown by the government, he told reporters. “Due to its extra caution, the Health Ministry tested body fluids of the man even after his blood tested negative for Ebola. I want to say the situation is under complete control. We have similar arrangements at 24 airports across the country,” he told reporters.
The tour and medical history of passengers are being checked at airports, he said. The man will remain quarantined at a special facility at Delhi airport so long as medical reports confirm that he is completely rid of the virus.
The man was treated for Ebola in Liberia and carried a certificate from authorities there that he was cured. The Ministry had said the man was already treated for the deadly disease in the African country and carried no symptoms but tests of his semen samples were positive, prompting authorities to put him under isolation.

RK News
Baghdad:  Dispelling rumors of his injury or death, the leader of Islamic State issued a new call to arms Thursday in a 17-minute speech, belittling President Barack Obama's plan to send more soldiers to Iraq and urging disciples to "erupt volcanoes of jihad everywhere." 
An audio recording of the speech by the leader, Abu Bakr al-Baghdadi, was distributed online, along with Arabic, English and Russian transcripts. It was first reported by the SITE Intelligence Group, a jihadi monitoring organization. 
Baghdadi's speech appeared to end days of rumors that he had been killed or grievously wounded in an airstrike carried out in northwestern Iraq on Saturday by the U.S. -led coalition fighting the Islamic State. 
With characteristic bluster, Baghdadi exhorted Muslims throughout the Middle East to rise up against "the agents of the Jews and crusaders, their slaves, tails and dogs." He declared, "We see America and her allies stumbling between fear, weakness, inability and failure."

2 militants killed in Kulgam encounter
RK News
Srinagar: Two militants were killed in an encounter with police and forces at Chenigam Kulgam.
As reported earlier regarding the presence of militants in village Chenigam, Frisal, Yaripora, Kulgam Police, 1 RR and 18 Bn CRPF launched a cordon and search operation on Thursday evening.
However, the joint party was fired upon by militants triggering an encounter in which two militants have been killed.

Relocation of polling stations in 10-Bandipora, 11-Sonawari
RK News
Bandipora: According to District Election Officer Bandipora, the Election Commission of India has accorded approval for change of location in respect four following polling stations in district Bandipora which were damaged in recent floods. 
Accordingly 17-Kema in 10-Bandipora Assembly segment has been relocated at Girls Middle School Kema instead of Boys Middle School Kema. While in 11-Sonawari Assembly segment polling station 20-Rakh Asham has been shifted to Middle School Gonchipora. Likewise, 42-Naidkhai-A has been shifted at Boys Middle School Bonapora (Naidkhai) instead of Boys Middle School Bathipora and 48 Naidkhai-G has been shifted at Girls High School Naidkhai instead of Boys Higher Secondary School Naidkhai.

Sakina Ittoo, Abdul Majeed and Imran Nabi Dar files nomination papers
RK News
Srinagar: National Conference Thursday said that National Conference was set to emerge yet again as the single largest party in the State post Assembly elections and would give many surprises to its opponents from South Kashmir. 
Speaking at a rally in Kulgam after NC candidates from Noorabad, Kulgam and Homshalibug filed their nomination papers, NC General Secretary Ali Mohammad Sagar said that PDP was facing a severe crisis within the party and a sharp backlash from the public for corruption cases, scams and scandals being unearthed against the party's candidates every passing day.

Srinagar: Chairman Hurriyat (G) Syed Ali Geelani has called for complete shutdown on November 20th against proposed visit of Narender Modi.

Pakistan successfully test fires Hatf-VI ballistic missile
RK News
Rawalpindi: Pakistan on Thursday conducted a successful training launch of intermediate range Shaheen-II (Hatf-VI) ballistic missile, the Inter Services Public Relations (ISPR) reported.
The successful launch was the culminating point of the Field Training Exercise of Army Strategic Forces Command.
Shaheen-II Missiles is capable of carrying nuclear and conventional warheads to a range of 1500 kilometers.

Ex NC MLA joins PDP
RK News
Baramulla:  Senior National Confrence leader and former MLA Ghulam Mohammad Lone Thursday joined People's Democratic Party here at party convention at Dak Banglow Baramulla.
He was a former MLA during 90s hailing from Ladoora Rafiabad. "I quit NC and have decided to join PDP. I am inspired by PDP's people friendly policies. NC has no agenda but corruption, dynastic rule and wrong policies," Lone said.

7 Army men convicted in Machil fake encounter
RK News
Srinagar: Seven Army men, including two officers have been convicted for their involvement in the 2010 Machil fake encounter case. The General Court Martial awarded life sentence to all convicts and has also suspended their service benefits.
The 2010 Machil fake encounter case had triggered widespread agitation in Kashmir. 
In 2010, three youth were gunned down in a staged encounter by troops near the Line of Control (LoC) in Kupwara district. The victims, who were from North Kashmir were lured to Kupwara with the promise of job and money, were dubbed as Pakistani militants who attempted to infiltrate.

BJP candidate escapes bid on life
RK News
Kulgam: With an intention to ‘assassinate’ the BJP candidate for Kulgam Constituency, unidentified gunmen raided his house located at Bogund on Tuesday night. The son of the BJP candidate Ghulam Hasan Zargar said that his father managed to hid himself in one of the dark corners of the house that saved his life.
 “The gunmen were four in number. Two of them entered into our house while rest of them took position on the gate. They were looking for my father and after not finding him in the room, they thrashed a worker mercilessly,” he said adding that before leaving the house they threatened us of dire consequences and said that they will kill Zargar today or tomorrow.
 The son of the BJP candidate added that the gunmen fired two shots in air before fleeing from the spot. “My father spent the night in police station and we are anxious about his security,” he said.
 Meanwhile a police official said that the security of the BJP candidate has been tightened and he is now safe and secure.

Tarigami files nominations
RK News
Kulgam: State Secretary CPI(M), Mohammad Yousuf Tarigami Wednesday filed his nomination papers in the office of Dy. Commissioner Kulgam. He was accompanied by Ghulam Hassan Mir, Hakeem Mohammad Yaseen, other prominent party leaders and large number of supporters. It may be recalled here that Tarigami is seeking mandate from the electorate of Kulgam constituency for fourth consecutive term, as he has retained the seat since 1996 continuously.

NC to form new JK Government: Omar
RK News
Ramban: Working President National Conference and Chief Minister, Omar Abdullah Wednesday said that National Conference will form the new government in Jammu and Kashmir by all means. He added that no government is possible in the State without the participation of National Conference. He said NC kept away from government formation in 2002 on its own decision otherwise it was in a position at that time too to form the government for being the majority party in the State Legislative Assembly.
“Day dreaming by PDP and BJP’s 44+ drama will end up in oblivion”, he said and added that dreaming, however, is not a banned commodity. He said that PDP is spreading falsehood and baseless propaganda while BJP is staging drama to create illusion and confusion among the voters. He said people of Jammu and Kashmir are wiser enough to read between the lines and understand the designs of these parties to create artificial hype for misleading public. He said the so-called poll analysis and predictions have nothing do with ground reality and the reality is that the National Conference is going to win the elections comfortably and with majority.
Omar Abdullah was addressing public meeting at Hall and Shamthi in Ramban Assembly Constituency organized by National Conference Jammu Province in favour of its contesting candidate Dr. Chaman Lal Bhagat today.

Doors open for Mehboob Beg: PDP
RK News
Anantnag: Amid rumours of Mehboob Beg of National Conference joining Peoples Democratic Party on Tuesday in South Kashmir’s Anantnag district, senior PDP leader and Parliament Member Muzaffar Hussain Baig said that Dr Mehboob Beg is always welcome and for him PDP doors are always open.
Baig was responding to a query raised by reporters whether Dr Mehboob Beg is mulling to join PDP at the sidelines of a party function at Dak Bungalow Anantnag.
 “Dr Mehboob Beg is an honest politician and a man of principle. PDP will welcome and is ready to hug him,” Beig said.

Nobody will be allowed to create disturbance in Assembly Elections: IGP
29 persons taken into preventive detention in Bandipora
RK News
Srinagar: Inspector General of Kashmir A G Mir Tuesday visited Bandipora and reviewed the security arrangements for the forthcoming assembly elections. The IGP chaired the security arrangements meeting. 
Speaking to the media after the security review meet, IGP said that after analysing the parliamentary elections and keeping the past experience in view all arrangements have been made for incident free assembly elections. He said that in order to ensure a peaceful atmosphere, 29 persons have been taken into preventive detention in Bandipora.
He said that everything possible under law shall be done and nobody shall be allowed to create any kind of disturbances during the elections.
He said that enough manpower and resources have been kept at the disposal of the districts for catering the needs of the security for electioneering and elections.

BJP announces five candidates for LA polls
RK News
Srinagar: The Central Election Committee of BJP has announced its list of five candidates who will contest Legislative Assembly elections. The candidates include Abdul Rehman Lone who will contest from Kupwara, Abdul Rashid Zargar
for Lolab, M.M. War for Langate, Ghulam Hassan Zargar for Kulgam and Dr. Nirmal Singh for Billawar.

Pakistan violates ceasefire 
RK News
Srinagar: There has been yet another ceasefire violation by Pakistan along the Line of Control in the Uri sector in Jammu and Kashmir.
Pakistani army reportedly resorted to firing at three Indian Army posts in the Kamalkot area along the LoC.
It is the second ceasefire violation in the same area in the last three days. On Saturday, an 18-year-old girl and a soldier were killed in firing in Uri.

Shutdown in Baramulla 
Syed Rizwan Geelani
Baramulla: A complete shutdown is observed in Baramulla town over the detention of a youth by JK Police.
According to locals, Police on Monday afternoon picked up a youth namely Sameer Gojri of Old town Baramulla for his involvement in stone pelting.
They said soon after shopkeepers opened their business establishments in Baramulla market some youth hurled stones on the shops and forced them to close down the shops. "Situation was very tense and we had no option but to close down the shops," said Junaid Ahmad, a local shopkeeper. 
All the shopkeepers are however waiting on pavements to open their shops. "We will open our shops according to situation. We can't take risk."
Meanwhile, sources said the detained youth in past has also injured a police personnel when they came to arrest him.
